# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alps
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alps/1924-winter-olympics] The **1924 Winter Olympics**, officially known as the **I Olympic Winter Games** (French: *Iers Jeux olympiques d'hiver*) and commonly known as **Chamonix 1924** (Arpitan: *Chamôni 1924*), were a winter multi-sport event which was held in 1924 in Chamonix, France.
[src:alps/1924-winter-olympics] Organized by the French Olympic Committee and held as part of an "International Winter Sports Week", the competitions took place in Chamonix and Haute-Savoie, France, from 25 January to 5 February 1924.
[src:alps/1924-winter-olympics] Although not initially termed "Winter Olympics", the International Olympic Committee (IOC) decided to retrospectively grant the Chamonix competitions the status of the first Winter Olympic Games at the committee's 26th session on May 6, 1926.
[src:alps/1924-winter-olympics] The tradition of holding the Winter Olympics in the same year as the Summer Olympics would continue until 1992, after which the current practice of holding a Winter Olympics in the second year after each Summer Olympics began.
[src:alps/1924-winter-olympics] Although figure skating had been an Olympic event in both London and Antwerp and ice hockey had been an event in Antwerp, winter sports had always been limited by the season.
[src:alps/1924-winter-olympics] At the 1921 IOC convention in Lausanne, there was a call for equality for winter sports.
[src:alps/1924-winter-olympics] After much discussion, it was decided that France, host nation for the 1924 Summer Olympics, would hold an "international week of winter sport" in Chamonix.
[src:alps/1924-winter-olympics] Charles Jewtraw of the United States won the first gold medal of the games in the 500-meter speed skate, making him the first Winter Olympic champion.
[src:alps/1924-winter-olympics] Sonja Henie of Norway, at just eleven years old, took part in the ladies' figure skating competition.
[src:alps/1924-winter-olympics] Although she finished last, she became popular with fans and went on to take gold at the following three Winter Olympics.
[src:alps/1924-winter-olympics] Figure skater Gillis Grafström of Sweden became the first athlete to successfully defend his Summer Olympic title at the Winter Olympics (having won a gold medal in 1920).
[src:alps/1924-winter-olympics] The Canadian ice hockey team (Toronto Granites) finished their qualifying round with three wins against Czechoslovakia (30–0), Sweden (22–0), and Switzerland (33–0), scoring a total of 85 goals and conceding none.
[src:alps/1924-winter-olympics] Finding themselves in the same situation as Gillis Grafström, the Canadian ice hockey team is the last to defend their Summer Olympics title at the Winter Olympics successfully.
[src:alps/1924-winter-olympics] Canada would dominate ice hockey in early Olympic competitions, winning six of the first seven gold medals awarded.
[src:alps/1924-winter-olympics] Taffy Abel (1900–1964) was an Indigenous Ojibwe ice hockey player.
[src:alps/1924-winter-olympics] He was the first Native American in the Winter Olympic Games (1924 Hockey Silver Medal), the 1924 Flag Bearer for the United States at the 1924 Winter Olympics, the first Native American in the National Hockey League (1926), and a Stanley Cup champion (1929 and 1934).
[src:alps/1924-winter-olympics] At the closing ceremony, a prize for alpinism, a sport not officially included in the Olympic Winter Games, was awarded by Pierre de Coubertin to Lt Col Edward Strutt, the deputy leader of British expedition, on behalf of their attempt to climb Mount Everest in 1922.
[src:alps/1924-winter-olympics] For the first time in the history of the modern Olympics, the host country (in this case, France) failed to win any gold medals, finishing with three bronze medals.
[src:alps/1924-winter-olympics] The same outcome occurred at the next Winter Olympics in St.
[src:alps/1924-winter-olympics] Moritz where Switzerland won only a single bronze medal, the lowest ever output by a host nation at an Olympics.
[src:alps/1924-winter-olympics] Later host nations to finish without gold medals included Canada at the 1976 Summer Olympics in Montreal, Yugoslavia at the 1984 Winter Olympics in Sarajevo, and Canada for a second time at the 1988 Winter Olympics in Calgary.
[src:alps/1924-winter-olympics] In 1925, the International Olympic Committee (IOC) decided to organize the Olympic Winter Games every four years, independent of the Olympic Games proper, and recognized the International Winter Sports Week as the first Olympic Winter Games in retrospect.
[src:alps/1924-winter-olympics] The final individual medal of Chamonix 1924 was presented in 1974.
[src:alps/1924-winter-olympics] The ski jumping event was unusual because the bronze medalist was not determined for fifty years.
[src:alps/1924-winter-olympics] On 12 September 1974, Anders Haugen, at the age of 85, came to Norway and was presented the bronze medal by Anna Maria Magnussen, Thorleif Haug's youngest daughter.
[src:alps/1924-winter-olympics] In 2006, the IOC confirmed that the medals awarded to the 1924 curling and military patrol teams were official.
[src:alps/1924-winter-olympics] The IOC verified that curling was officially part of the program, after the *Glasgow Herald* newspaper filed a claim on behalf of the families of the team.
[src:alps/1924-winter-olympics] Medals were awarded in 16 events contested in 5 sports (9 disciplines).
[src:alps/1924-winter-olympics] Many sources do not list curling and the military patrol as Olympic events, or list them as demonstration events.
[src:alps/1924-winter-olympics] However, no such designation was made in 1924.
[src:alps/1924-winter-olympics] In February 2006, the International Olympic Committee (IOC) ruled that curling and military patrol were part of the Olympic program, and have included the medals awarded in the official count.
[src:alps/1924-winter-olympics] Athletes from 16 nations competed in the first Winter Olympic Games.
[src:alps/1924-winter-olympics] Germany was banned from competing in the games, and instead hosted a series of games called Deutsche Kampfspiele.
[src:alps/1924-winter-olympics] Pierre de Coubertin—founder of the IOC & father of the modern Olympics movement—personally awarded, in addition to the medals awarded in the sports competitions, 21 gold medals to members of the 1922 British Mount Everest Expedition including 12 Britons, 7 Indians, 1 Australian and 1 Nepalese.
[src:alps/1924-winter-olympics] Only the gold medal from 1924 is assigned to the Winter Olympics by the IOC in its database to the Mixed team, while the medals from 1932 and 1936 are assigned to the Summer Olympics for the respective NOCs.
[src:alps/1928-winter-olympics] The **1928 Winter Olympics**, officially known as the **II Olympic Winter Games** (French: *IIes Jeux olympiques d'hiver*; German: *II.
[src:alps/1928-winter-olympics] Olympische Winterspiele*; Italian: *II Giochi olimpici invernali*; Romansh: *II Gieus olimpics d'enviern*) and commonly known as **St.
[src:alps/1928-winter-olympics] Moritz 1928** (French: *Saint-Moritz 1928*; Romansh: *San Murezzan 1928*), were an international winter multi-sport event that was celebrated from 11 to 19 February 1928 in St.
[src:alps/1928-winter-olympics] The 1928 Games were the first true Winter Olympics to be held as a stand-alone event, not in conjunction with a Summer Olympics.
[src:alps/1928-winter-olympics] The preceding 1924 Winter Games were retroactively renamed the inaugural Winter Olympics, although they had in fact been organised alongside the 1924 Summer Olympics in France.
[src:alps/1928-winter-olympics] Before 1924, the winter events were included in the schedule of the Summer Games and there were no separate Winter Games.
[src:alps/1928-winter-olympics] The 1928 Winter Games also replaced the now redundant Nordic Games, which had been held at varying intervals since early in the 20th century.
[src:alps/1928-winter-olympics] The hosts were challenged by fluctuating weather conditions; the opening ceremony was held in a blizzard, while warm weather conditions plagued sporting events throughout the rest of the Games.
[src:alps/1928-winter-olympics] The 10,000 metre speed-skating event was controversially abandoned and officially cancelled.
[src:alps/1928-winter-olympics] Filmed footage of the games exists in a silent, feature-length documentary, *The White Stadium*.
[src:alps/1928-winter-olympics] Medals were awarded in 14 events contested in 4 sports (8 disciplines).
[src:alps/1928-winter-olympics] Athletes from 25 nations competed at these Games, up from 16 in 1924.
[src:alps/1928-winter-olympics] Nations making their first appearance at the Winter Olympic Games were Argentina (first participation of a delegation coming from a country belonging to the Southern Hemisphere), Estonia, Germany, Japan, Lithuania, Luxembourg, Mexico, the Netherlands, and Romania.
[src:alps/1936-winter-olympics] The **1936 Winter Olympics**, officially the **IV Olympic Winter Games** (German: *IV.
[src:alps/1936-winter-olympics] Olympische Winterspiele*) and commonly known as **Garmisch-Partenkirchen 1936**, were a winter multi-sport event held from 6 to 16 February 1936 in Garmisch-Partenkirchen, Germany.
[src:alps/1936-winter-olympics] They were the fourth edition of the Winter Olympic Games and the first to be held in Germany.
[src:alps/1936-winter-olympics] Later the same year the country also hosted the 1936 Summer Olympics in Berlin; 1936 was the last year in which one nation staged both the Summer and Winter Games.
[src:alps/1936-winter-olympics] The Games were organised on behalf of the German League of the Reich for Physical Exercise by Karl Ritter von Halt.
[src:alps/1936-winter-olympics] Staged in a Germany governed by the Nazi Party, they prompted international boycott efforts; the regime temporarily removed antisemitic signage and, under outside pressure, allowed the Jewish ice hockey player Rudi Ball to compete for Germany.
[src:alps/1936-winter-olympics] Within weeks of the closing ceremony, German forces remilitarized the Rhineland.
[src:alps/1936-winter-olympics] A then-record 28 nations and 646 athletes took part.
[src:alps/1936-winter-olympics] They contested 17 events across four sports, with alpine skiing making its Olympic debut.
[src:alps/1936-winter-olympics] Norway led the medal table with seven gold medals.
[src:alps/1936-winter-olympics] Among the standout performers were Norway's Ivar Ballangrud, who won three of the four speed-skating titles, and figure skater Sonja Henie, who took her third consecutive Olympic gold, while Great Britain upset defending champions Canada to win the ice hockey tournament.
[src:alps/1936-winter-olympics] At its 29th Session in Barcelona in 1931, the International Olympic Committee (IOC) awarded the 1936 Summer Olympics to Berlin.
[src:alps/1936-winter-olympics] Under the rules then in force, the country hosting the Summer Games was also expected, where possible, to stage the Winter Games earlier in the same year.
[src:alps/1936-winter-olympics] The Bavarian towns of Garmisch and Partenkirchen, at the foot of the Zugspitze, were put forward as hosts, and the choice was confirmed by the IOC at its 31st Session in Vienna on 7 June 1933.
[src:alps/1936-winter-olympics] Adolf Hitler had become German chancellor in January that year.
[src:alps/1936-winter-olympics] In preparation for the Games, the two towns were merged into a single municipality, Garmisch-Partenkirchen, on 1 January 1935.
[src:alps/1936-winter-olympics] The Games were organised by Karl Ritter von Halt, who had been appointed head of the organising committee by Reichssportführer Hans von Tschammer und Osten.
[src:alps/1936-winter-olympics] According to historians Arnd Krüger and William Murray, Nazi interest in winter sport was encouraged in part by its promotion in Mussolini's Italy, where skiing had been marketed to the middle class.
[src:alps/1936-winter-olympics] Because the Games were held in a state governed by the openly antisemitic Nazi regime, several countries debated boycotting both the Winter and Summer Olympics, and some Jewish athletes faced pressure not to take part.
[src:alps/1936-winter-olympics] Before foreign visitors arrived, the authorities temporarily removed antisemitic signs from the host towns and—under pressure linked to a possible American boycott—allowed Rudi Ball, the only Jewish athlete on the German team, to play in the ice hockey tournament.
[src:alps/1936-winter-olympics] Shortly before the opening, IOC president Henri de Baillet-Latour reminded Hitler that the Games were to be kept free of political propaganda and conducted under the IOC's rules.
[src:alps/1936-winter-olympics] No nation boycotted the Winter Games, and the 28 that competed were the most at any Winter Olympics up to that point.
[src:alps/1936-winter-olympics] The competition passed with little overt political controversy, although the Canadian team's raised-arm "Olympic salute" during the opening ceremony was mistaken by spectators for the Nazi salute.
[src:alps/1936-winter-olympics] The Große Olympiaschanze ski jump was built for the Games, and the adjoining ski stadium staged the opening and closing ceremonies, the cross-country races and the ski-jumping events.
[src:alps/1936-winter-olympics] A financial statement compiled in April 1936 showed that both spending and income had more than doubled the organising committee's original 1933 estimates of around one million Reichsmark (RM) each.
[src:alps/1936-winter-olympics] Total expenditure came to 2,618,259 RM, of which about 1,257,000 RM was spent on building and enlarging the sports venues and 1,099,000 RM on organisation and administration; the remainder covered items such as propaganda, temporary barracks and clean-up.
[src:alps/1936-winter-olympics] Income totalled 2,415,369 RM, including 1,253,831 RM in grants from the Garmisch and Partenkirchen municipalities, the city of Munich, the Bavarian state and the German government, and 1,010,618 RM from ticket sales.
[src:alps/1936-winter-olympics] Spending thus exceeded income by 202,890 RM, a shortfall the German government undertook to cover.
[src:alps/1936-winter-olympics] Much larger sums were spent outside the committee's accounts by the state railway, post office and broadcasting service, and on a new trunk road and the partial double-tracking of the Munich–Garmisch railway.
[src:alps/1936-winter-olympics] The Games attracted the largest crowds of any Winter Olympics up to that point; one study judges that more people attended than at all the previous Winter Games combined.
[src:alps/1936-winter-olympics] On ordinary competition days between 35,000 and 50,000 spectators were present in Garmisch-Partenkirchen, rising to about 64,000 on the first Sunday and an estimated 150,000 on the closing day, 16 February.
[src:alps/1936-winter-olympics] Between 5 and 17 February the state railway carried roughly 250,000 people to and from the town and the post office a further 13,000 by bus, while about 10,000 motor vehicles were in the town on the final day.
[src:alps/1936-winter-olympics] Special trains left Munich at intervals as short as ten minutes through the night, and directing the traffic on the narrow Alpine roads required several hundred police and auxiliaries.
[src:alps/1936-winter-olympics] The Games also brought communications innovations.
[src:alps/1936-winter-olympics] The opening ceremony took place on 6 February 1936 before a crowd of more than 30,000.
[src:alps/1936-winter-olympics] Cross-country skier Willy Bogner took the Olympic Oath on behalf of the competitors.
[src:alps/1936-winter-olympics] Alpine skiing appeared at the Olympics for the first time, contested as a combined event scoring each competitor's downhill and slalom runs; the German skiers Franz Pfnür and Christl Cranz won the men's and women's titles.
[src:alps/1936-winter-olympics] A dispute between the International Ski Federation and the IOC over whether ski instructors could be regarded as amateurs led the Swiss and Austrian teams to boycott the alpine events.
[src:alps/1936-winter-olympics] On the speed-skating oval, Norway's Ivar Ballangrud won three of the four races.
[src:alps/1936-winter-olympics] Sonja Henie of Norway secured her third consecutive Olympic title in figure skating.
[src:alps/1936-winter-olympics] Switzerland won the four-man bobsled in a combined time of 5:19.85, and Norway topped the overall medal table with seven gold, five silver and three bronze medals.
[src:alps/1936-winter-olympics] The ice hockey tournament produced the Games' most contentious episode.
[src:alps/1936-winter-olympics] Most of the British team had learned the game in Canada, and Canada, the reigning Olympic champion, protested the inclusion of two of them—goaltender Jimmy Foster and forward Alex Archer—on the grounds that, having joined English clubs, they should be treated as professionals.
[src:alps/1936-winter-olympics] The protest was withdrawn partway through the tournament as a gesture of goodwill, a concession Canada came to regret: with Foster in goal, Great Britain beat Canada 2–1—Edgar Brenchley scored the winning goal—and took the gold medal, ending Canada's run of four consecutive Olympic titles.
[src:alps/1936-winter-olympics] Because the Olympic tournament also counted as that year's World Championship, the British side became the first European team to be crowned world champions.
[src:alps/1936-winter-olympics] The medals presented at the Games were the largest and heaviest awarded at any Olympics up to that date, measuring 100 mm in diameter and 4 mm thick.
[src:alps/1936-winter-olympics] A total of 28 National Olympic Committees sent athletes to the Games.
[src:alps/1936-winter-olympics] Australia, Bulgaria, Greece, Liechtenstein, Spain and Turkey made their Winter Olympic debuts, while Estonia, Latvia, Luxembourg, the Netherlands and Yugoslavia returned after missing the 1932 Winter Olympics.
[src:alps/1936-winter-olympics] The ten nations that won medals at the 1936 Winter Games are listed below; the host nation (Germany) is highlighted.
[src:alps/1936-winter-olympics] Norway and Sweden each completed a podium sweep at the Games: Norway in the Nordic combined (Oddbjørn Hagen, Olaf Hoffsbakken and Sverre Brodahl), and Sweden in the men's 50 km cross-country (Elis Wiklund, Axel Wikström and Nils-Joel Englund).
[src:alps/1936-winter-olympics] The 1936 Winter Games let German organisers rehearse arrangements for security, transport, communications and crowd control that were used again at the Summer Olympics in Berlin.
[src:alps/1936-winter-olympics] On the strength of the event, the IOC awarded the 1940 Winter Olympics to Garmisch-Partenkirchen, although those Games were cancelled after the outbreak of the Second World War.
[src:alps/1936-winter-olympics] On 7 March 1936, less than three weeks after the closing ceremony, Hitler ordered the Remilitarization of the Rhineland, his first open breach of the Treaty of Versailles.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] An institutional referendum (Italian: *referendum istituzionale*, or *referendum sulla forma istituzionale dello Stato*) was held by universal suffrage in the Kingdom of Italy on 2 June 1946, a key event of contemporary Italian history.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Until 1946, Italy was a kingdom ruled by the House of Savoy, reigning since the unification of Italy in 1861 and previously rulers of the Kingdom of Sardinia.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In 1922, the rise of Benito Mussolini and the creation of the Fascist regime in Italy, which eventually resulted in engaging the country in World War II alongside Nazi Germany, considerably weakened the role of the royal house.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Following the Italian Civil War and the Liberation of Italy from Axis troops in 1945, a popular referendum on the institutional form of the state was called the next year and resulted in voters choosing the replacement of the monarchy with a republic.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The 1946 Italian general election to elect the Constituent Assembly of Italy was held on the same day.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] As with the simultaneous Constituent Assembly elections, the referendum was not held in the Julian March, in the province of Zara or the province of Bolzano, which were still under occupation by Allied forces pending a final settlement of the status of the territories.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The results were proclaimed by the Supreme Court of Cassation on 10 June 1946: 12,717,923 citizens in favor of the republic and 10,719,284 citizens in favor of the monarchy.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The event is commemorated annually by the *Festa della Repubblica*.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] With the entry into force of the new Constitution of the Italian Republic, on 1 January 1948, Enrico De Nicola became the first to assume the functions of president of Italy.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] It marked the first time that most of the Italian Peninsula was under a single republican government since the fall of the Roman Republic.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In the history of Italy there are several so-called "republican" governments that have followed one another over time.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Examples are the ancient Roman Republic and the medieval maritime republics.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] From Cicero to Niccolò Machiavelli, Italian philosophers have imagined the foundations of political science and republicanism.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] But it was Giuseppe Mazzini who revived the republican idea in Italy in the 19th century.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] An Italian nationalist in the historical radical tradition and a proponent of a republicanism of social-democratic inspiration, Mazzini helped define the modern European movement for popular democracy in a republican state.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Mazzini formulated a concept known as "thought and action" in which thought and action must be joined and every thought must be followed by action, therefore rejecting intellectualism and the notion of divorcing theory from practice.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The foundation of the Young Italy constitutes a key moment of the Italian Risorgimento and this republican program precedes in time the proposals for the unification of Italy of Vincenzo Gioberti and Cesare Balbo, aimed at reunifying the Italian territory under the presidency of the Pope.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Subsequently, the philosopher Carlo Cattaneo promoted a secular and republican Italy in the extension of Mazzini's ideas, but organized as a federal republic.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The political projects of Mazzini and Cattaneo were thwarted by the action of the Piedmontese Prime Minister Camillo Benso, Count of Cavour, and Giuseppe Garibaldi.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The latter set aside his republican ideas to favor Italian unity.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] After having obtained the conquest of the whole of southern Italy during the Expedition of the Thousand, Garibaldi handed over the conquered territories to the king of Sardinia Victor Emmanuel II, which were annexed to the Kingdom of Sardinia after a plebiscite.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] This earned him heavy criticism from numerous republicans who accused him of treason.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] While a laborious administrative unification began, a first Italian parliament was elected and, on 17 March 1861, Victor Emmanuel II was proclaimed king of Italy.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] From 1861 to 1946, Italy was a constitutional monarchy founded on the Albertine Statute, named after the king who promulgated it in 1848, Charles Albert of Sardinia.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The parliament included a Senate, whose members were appointed by the king, and a Chamber of Deputies, elected by census vote.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In 1861 only 2% of Italians had the right to vote.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In the political panorama of the time there was a republican political movement which had its martyrs, such as the soldier Pietro Barsanti.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Barsanti was a supporter of republican ideas, and was a soldier in the Royal Italian Army with the rank of corporal.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] He was sentenced to death and shot in 1870 for having favored an insurrectional attempt against the Savoy monarchy and is therefore considered the first martyr of the modern Italian Republic and a symbol of republican ideals in Italy.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The balance of power between the Chamber and Senate initially shifted in favor of the Senate, composed mainly of nobles and industrial figures.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Little by little, the Chamber of Deputies took on more and more importance with the evolution of the bourgeoisie and the large landowners, concerned with economic progress, but supporters of order and a certain social conservatism.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The Republicans took part in the elections to the Italian Parliament, and in 1853 they formed the Action Party around Giuseppe Mazzini.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Although in exile, Mazzini was elected in 1866, but refused to take his seat in parliament.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Carlo Cattaneo was elected deputy in 1860 and 1867, but refused so as not to have to swear loyalty to the House of Savoy.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The problem of the oath of loyalty to the monarchy, necessary to be elected, was the subject of controversy within the republican forces.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In 1873 Felice Cavallotti, one of the most committed Italian politicians against the monarchy, preceded his oath with a declaration in which he reaffirmed his republican beliefs.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In 1882, a new electoral law lowered the census limit for voting rights, increasing the number of voters to over two million, equal to 7% of the population.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In the same year the Italian Workers' Party was created, which in 1895 became the Italian Socialist Party.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In 1895 the intransigent republicans agreed to participate in the political life of the Kingdom, establishing the Italian Republican Party.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Two years later, the far left reached its historical maximum level in Parliament with 81 deputies, for the three radical-democratic, socialist components and Republican.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] With the death of Felice Cavallotti in 1898, the radical left gave up on posing the institutional problem.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In Italian politics, the socialist party progressively divided into two tendencies: a maximalist one, led among others by Arturo Labriola and Enrico Ferri, and supporting the use of strikes; the other, reformist and pro-government, was led by Filippo Turati.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] A nationalist movement emerged, led in particular by Enrico Corradini, as well as a Catholic social and democratic movement, the National Democratic League, led by Romolo Murri.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In 1904, Pope Pius X authorized Catholics to participate individually in political life, but in 1909 he condemned the National Democratic League created by Romolo Murri, who was excommunicated.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Finally, a law of 3 June 1912 marked Italy's evolution towards a certain political liberalism by establishing universal male suffrage.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In 1914, at the outbreak of World War I, Italy began to be counted among the world's liberal democracies.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] After World War I, Italian political life was animated by four great movements.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Two of these movements were in favor of democratic development within the framework of existing monarchical institutions: the reformist socialists and the Italian People's Party.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Two other movements challenged these institutions: the Republican Party on the one hand, and the maximalist socialists.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In the 1919 elections, the parties most imbued with republican ideology (the maximalist socialists and the Republican Party) won, obtaining 165 out of 508 seats in the Chamber of Deputies.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In the 1921 elections, after the foundation of the Italian Communist Party, the three parties republican, maximalist socialist and communist obtained 145 deputies out of 535.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Overall, at the beginning of the interwar period, less than 30% of those elected were in favor of the establishment of a republican regime.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In this context, the rise of Benito Mussolini's fascist movement was based on the bitterness generated by the "mutilated victory", the fear of social unrest and the rejection of revolutionary, republican and Marxist ideology.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The liberal political system and part of the aristocracy chose to erect fascism as a bulwark against, in their way of seeing, these dangers.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In October 1922, the nomination of Benito Mussolini as prime minister by King Victor Emmanuel III, following the march on Rome, paved the way for the establishment of the dictatorship.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The Albertine Statute was progressively emptied of its content.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Parliament was subject to the will of the new government.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] On 27 June 1924, 127 deputies left Parliament and retreated to the Aventine Hill, a clumsy maneuver which, in effect, left the field open to the fascists.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] They then had the fate of Italy in their hands for two decades.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Not only did Victor Emmanuel III appeal to Mussolini to form the government in 1922 and allow him to proceed with the domestication of Parliament, but he did not even draw the consequences of the assassination of Giacomo Matteotti in 1924.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] He accepted the title of emperor in 1936 at the end of Second Italo-Ethiopian War, then the alliance with Nazi Germany and Italy's entry into World War II on 10 June 1940.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] With the implementation of fascist laws (Royal Decree of 6 November 1926), all political parties operating on Italian territory were dissolved, with the exception of the National Fascist Party.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Some of these parties expatriated and reconstituted themselves abroad, especially in France.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Some movements remained outside, including the Italian Communist Party, the popular Catholic movement and other liberal movements.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] This coalition dissolved on 5 May 1934 and, in August of the same year, the pact of unity of action was signed between the Italian Socialist Party and the Italian Communist Party.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In the meantime, in Italy, clandestine anti-fascist nuclei were formed, in particular in Milan with Ferruccio Parri and in Florence with Riccardo Bauer.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Under the impetus of these groups, the Action Party, Mazzini's former republican party, was re-established.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Between the end of 1942 and the beginning of 1943, Alcide De Gasperi wrote *The reconstructive ideas of Christian Democracy*, which laid the foundations of the new Catholic-inspired party, the Christian Democracy.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] It brought together the veterans of Luigi Sturzo's Italian People's Party and the young people of Catholic associations, in particular of the University Federation.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] On 10 July 1943, the Allies landed in Sicily in Operation Husky.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] On 25 July 1943, Victor Emmanuel III revoked Mussolini's mandate as prime minister and had him arrested, entrusting the government to Marshal Pietro Badoglio.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The new government contacted the Allies to reach an armistice.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] When the Armistice of Cassibile was announced on 8 September 1943, the Germans reacted by placing under their control all the part of Italian territory that still escaped the Allied advance and by disarming the Italian Royal Army.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Victor Emmanuel III and Badoglio's government fled Rome and reached Brindisi, in southern Italy.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In these dramatic circumstances, in the two territories the civil administration gave way to a military and police administration.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] However, the parties that existed before fascism were reconstituted, alongside new political parties.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] On 9 September 1943, in Rome (still occupied by the Germans), a National Liberation Committee (CLN) was created, which brought together the parties and movements opposed to fascism and German occupation.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] It was made up of representatives of the Italian Communist Party, members of the Action Party, Christian Democrats, liberals, socialists and progressive democrats.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The patriotic war of liberation led by the National Liberation Committee was also, for a significant part of its supporters, a war of social liberation, a war against a collaborationist elite.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] However, the Americans and English, anxious to prepare for the post-war period, facilitated the entry into German-occupied territory of Italian democratic and republican activists aimed at counterbalancing the communist influence in the leadership of the National Liberation Committee.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] This was the case, for example, of Leo Valiani, future member of the triumvirate responsible for the partisan insurrection in Piedmont and Lombardy.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] On 31 March 1944, in Salerno, Palmiro Togliatti, general secretary of the Italian Communist Party, called for the formation of a government of national unity and no longer required the king's abdication as a prerequisite.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] This declaration pushed the parties of the National Liberation Committee to rally around a compromise drawn up by Enrico De Nicola, president of the Chamber of Deputies until 1924, by Benedetto Croce of the liberal party and by the king's entourage.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] As foreseen in this agreement, upon the liberation of Rome, on 4 June 1944, Victor Emmanuel III proclaimed his son Umberto lieutenant general of the kingdom, and the parties took political control of the nation, even if the war continued, stabilizing on the front on the Gothic line until April 1945.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] From June 1944 to December 1945, three provisional coalition governments followed one another.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The first was led by Ivanoe Bonomi, of the Labour Democratic Party.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] His government included the anti-fascist liberals Carlo Sforza and Benedetto Croce, as well as Palmiro Togliatti.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Although temporarily put aside, the question of Italian institutions remained one of the main open political questions.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Most of the forces supporting the National Liberation Committee were openly republicans and believed that the monarchy, in particular Victor Emmanuel III, had had a responsibility in the success of the fascist movement.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The final agreement between the parties was to ask that at the end of the war, as soon as conditions were favourable, the calling of elections, an institutional referendum and the formation of a constituent assembly.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Until then, on 31 January 1945, the Council of Ministers, chaired by Ivanoe Bonomi, issued a decree which recognized women's right to vote.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Universal suffrage was thus recognized, after the vain attempts made in 1881 and 1907 by women of the various parties.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The Bonomi governments (II then III) were succeeded by the Parri government in June 1945, then by the First De Gasperi government in December 1945.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The question of the future form of the state, monarchy or republic, absorbed the minds of political circles.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The majority of Christian Democratic activists, especially young people, increasingly distanced themselves from the monarchy.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] During the local meetings of the leaders of this party, in Rome and Milan, motions were presented aimed at making official a political line favorable to a democratic republic.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The central political office tried to curb these pressures and maintain an intermediate position.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] On 16 March 1946, Prince Umberto decreed, as expected in 1944, that the question of the institutional form of the state would be decided by a referendum organized simultaneously with the election of a constituent assembly.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The Supreme Court of Cassation was responsible for examining the appeals.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Its role was to be limited to observing the progress of voting operations and consolidating the bulletins issued by the offices that communicated the results in each constituency.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The counting of the ballots of the candidates for the constituent assembly had to precede that of the referendum.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] If the monarchy had won, it would have been the Constituent Assembly that would have had to choose the head of state.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Wanted by the Allies to verify that the conditions existed for voting in a country torn apart by the civil war only a few months earlier, partial municipal and provincial elections were held in March and April 1946 in half of the Italian municipalities and provinces.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] These elections, which mainly involved left-wing cities, brought out three parties, with a clear advantage for the Christian Democrats, led by Alcide De Gasperi, which exceeded the sum of votes cast for the Italian Communist Party and the Italian Socialist Party.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] After these administrative elections, the monarchists, already worried about the outcome of the referendum, became even more discouraged.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] But a political event changed the situation during the referendum campaign.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] A month before the referendum, Victor Emmanuel III abdicated in favor of his son Umberto, who was proclaimed king and took the name Umberto II.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The act of abdication, drawn up privately, is dated 9 May 1946.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] This abdication was desired by the monarchists, since the crown prince was less compromised than his father in Mussolini's rise to power and in coexistence with the fascist forces.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] It is also possible that the command of the allied forces present on Italian territory encouraged the sovereign to abdicate in favor of his son.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The former king immediately left Italy for Alexandria in Egypt.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Umberto II confirmed his promise to respect the popular decision regarding the referendum.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The representatives of the parties in favor of the Republic protested, arguing the assumption of royal powers by the lieutenant general conflicted with an article of the legislative decree of 16 March 1946 that aimed at guaranteeing institutional stability before the announcement of the results.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] For observers, the gap between republicans and monarchists was narrowing, which increased tension in the final phase of the electoral campaign.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In fact, some scuffles broke out between activists of the two sides in the tense climate.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The vote for the choice between monarchy or republic took place on 2 June and on the morning of 3 June 1946.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] After the transfer of the electoral cards from all of Italy and the minutes of the 31 constituencies to Rome, the results were expected on 8 June.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] On 10 June, the still provisional results were announced, and the final ones were communicated later due to missing data in some polling stations and after the examination of numerous appeals regarding the contested referendum ballots.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In fact, 21,000 disputes occurred over the referendum ballots, most of which were quickly resolved.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] However, the period of uncertainty between the end of the vote and the final official announcement of the results only strengthened tensions in the country.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In the city of Naples, in Apulia, in Calabria and in Sicily, the monarchists carried out protest demonstrations, sometimes violent.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] On 7 June, a monarchist student, soon transformed into a martyr, was killed.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] One of the complaints submitted to the Supreme Court of Cassation is particularly delicate.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] This controversy was over the definition of "majority".
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The monarchists believed that it was necessary to take into account not the majority of votes cast, but the "majority of electors", as an article of the electoral law provided.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The public prosecutor of the Supreme Court of Cassation, Massimo Pilotti, deemed this appeal admissible.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In his indictment Pilotti believed that the spirit and letter of the decrees as well as jurisprudence provide for the counting of voters, without excluding blank or invalid ballots.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] But the Supreme Court of Cassation ruled against him, with 12 votes against to 7.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] On the one hand, it was believed that the vote, as a legal act, manifested a will and that the blank or null vote could be assimilated to the absence of expression of will.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The Supreme Court of Cassation also identified another decree which specified that only "validly cast" votes should be preserved.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The Supreme Court of Cassation finally announced that no law or decree dealt with the need for an absolute majority.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The final results were announced on 18 June 1946.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Voter turnout was 89%, with 54% of the votes cast for the republic and 46% for the monarchy.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The analysis of the data by region showed an Italy practically divided in two: in the north the republic won with 66% of the votes cast, and the monarchy in the south with 64% of the votes.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] However, some voters were unable to vote.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Before the closure of the electoral lists in April 1945, many Italian soldiers were still outside the national territory, in detention or internment camps abroad.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] These provinces, however, were all located in the north of the country, an area where the Republican vote obtained a fairly large majority.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The conservative, rural *Mezzogiorno* (southern Italy) region voted solidly for the monarchy (63.8%) while the more urbanised and industrialised *Nord* (northern Italy) voted equally firmly for a republic (66.2%).
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The referendum was not held in the Julian March, in the province of Zara or the province of Bolzano, which were still under occupation by Allied forces pending a final settlement of the status of the territories.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] At first glance, the referendum seemed to simply divide Italy in two, between North and South, but the situation was more complex.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] For example, the districts located to the north of Rome gave the majority to the republic, while those located to the south chose the monarchy.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The electoral college of Rome was very divided and gave a slight majority to the choice of the monarchic regime.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The Republican choice turned into a plebiscite, with over 80% of the votes cast in the electoral college of Bologna, and even more in that of Trento.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In the South, however, the monarchist choice reached nearly 80% in the college of Naples.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] But, in other regions, the vote was very fragmented.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] There was not a total break with the past, but an interference between the two possible choices, which was expressed everywhere.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The occupation of the North by the German forces and the period of the Italian Civil War, with the fascist forces, undoubtedly favored an increase in the importance of the socialist and communist parties in this region, which were republican in tendency.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] During these dark years, the populations concerned placed part of their hopes in dreams of revolution, or at least of change.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The South, not having experienced this situation and having welcomed King Victor Emmanuel III and his government, was perhaps more wary of these parties and placed its trust in the monarchic regime, preferring continuity to the "leap into the unknown" represented by the republican form.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Furthermore, the clientelism prevalent in the South favored a vote that tended to be conservative, and therefore monarchist.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Some analysts also cite the influence of the Catholic Church or the Catholic press.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Other authors have highlighted more structural factors, such as differences in family organization or production by region.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Thus Carlo Bacetti compared, in Tuscany, the importance of metayage in the organization of work on the land, and the weight of the Communist Party in this region, which had republican tendencies.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] At the same time, republican demonstrations took place in many cities.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The Milanese newspaper, *Corriere della Sera*, on Tuesday 11 June, ran the headline: "The Italian Republic is born".
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] *La Stampa*, a Turin daily newspaper, declared more soberly: "The government confirms the victory of the republicans", and completed its coverage by asking: "the question is whether the republic has been proclaimed or not".
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In Naples, a city with a population largely supportive of the monarchy, an incident occurred on 11 June.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] A procession of supporters of the monarchy advanced towards the municipal buildings and then changed objective and headed towards the headquarters of the Italian Communist Party.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The crowd saw a red flag, but also a tricolor flag from which the royal coat of arms had been cut.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Despite the presence of armored vehicles, the demonstrators attempted to storm the communist party headquarters.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Protesters and law enforcement officers exchange gunfire.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] According to the prefect's report, the demonstrators shot first.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In any case the response was deadly, with machine gun fire.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] There were nine deaths among royalist demonstrators and a large number of injuries.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Calm returned to the city only on 13 June.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] On the night of 12 June, the government met at Alcide De Gasperi's invitation.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The Prime Minister received a written communication from the King, in which he said he was ready to respect the verdict of the electors' vote, but adding that he would await the final declaration of the Supreme Court of Cassation.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The letter and the protests of the monarchists, like the bloody events of the day before in Naples, as well as the new demonstrations announced by the monarchists worried the ministers.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The Prime Minister collected all the votes of the government members, with the exception of the liberal minister Leone Cattani.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Although some members of his entourage encouraged him to oppose this decision, the king, informed, decided to leave the country the following day, thus making a peaceful transfer of power possible, not without having denounced De Gasperi's "revolutionary gesture".
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] He went into exile in Cascais, Portugal.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] On the same day as the former king's departure, the flag of Italy with the Savoy coat of arms in the centre was lowered from the Quirinal Palace.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The Italian flag was modified with the decree of the president of the Council of Ministers No.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Compared to the monarchic banner, the Savoy coat of arms was eliminated.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The Republican tricolour was then officially and solemnly delivered to the Italian military corps on 4 November 1947 on the occasion of National Unity and Armed Forces Day.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The universally adopted ratio is 2:3, while the war flag is squared (1:1).
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Each *comune* also has a *gonfalone* bearing its coat of arms.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] On 27 May 1949, a law was passed that described and regulated the way the flag was displayed outside public buildings and during national holidays.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] After the birth of the Italian Republic, "La leggenda del Piave" was temporarily chosen as the provisional national anthem, which replaced "Marcia Reale", the national anthem of the Kingdom of Italy.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The political class of the time then approved the proposal of the War Minister Cipriano Facchinetti, who foresaw the adoption of "Il Canto degli Italiani" as a provisional anthem of the State.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] "Il Canto degli Italiani" was therefore chosen, on 12 October 1946, as the provisional national anthem, a role that it later preserved while remaining the de facto anthem of the Italian Republic.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Over the decades there were several unsuccessful attempts to make it the official national anthem, until it finally gained official status on 4 December 2017.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] On 18 June 1946 at 6 pm, in the Sala della Lupa of Palazzo Montecitorio in Rome, the Supreme Court of Cassation proceeded to proclaim the results of the referendum, without accompanying this formalization with reservations as it had done previously.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In the first session of the Constituent Assembly, on 28 June 1946, Enrico De Nicola was elected provisional head of the State, in the first round with 396 votes out of 501.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In addition to his personal qualities, the choice of a man born in Naples and long monarchic history, it was a sign of pacification and union towards the populations of southern Italy, in this accelerated transition towards the Republic.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] He was initially only provisional head of state and not president of Italy, since the latter did not yet have a constitution.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Alcide De Gasperi resigned and then regained the task of forming a new government, thus becoming the last Prime Minister of the monarchic era and the first of republican Italy.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] On 1 January 1948, the Republican Constitution came into force, the content of which was discussed within the Constituent Assembly.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] It proclaims in particular that "Italy is a democratic republic founded on labour" and that "the former kings of the House of Savoy, their wives and their male descendants are prohibited from entering and staying in the national territory".
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Enrico De Nicola then assumed the title of President of Italy.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The validity of the provision that prohibited the entry in Italy of some members of the House of Savoy ceased with the entry into force of the Constitutional Law of 23 October 2002, No.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] 1, after a debate in parliament and in the country that lasted many years and Vittorio Emanuele, Prince of Naples, son of King Umberto II, was able to enter Italy with his family already in the following December for a short visit.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The former queen Marie-José had already been authorized to return to Italy in 1987 since, with the death of her husband Umberto II and having become a widow, her status as "spouse" was recognized as having ceased.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The photo, which later became a "symbol" of the celebrations for the outcome of the referendum, portrays the face of a young woman emerging from a copy of *Il Corriere della Sera* of 6 June 1946 with the title «*È nata la Repubblica Italiana*» ("The Italian Republic is born").
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The symbolic photo of the birth of the Republic was taken by Federico Patellani for the weekly *Tempo* (n.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] 22, 15–22 June 1946) as part of a photo shoot celebrating the Republic and the new role of women; it was also featured on the front page of the *Il Corriere della Sera* itself and was later reused in many campaigns and posters.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Only in 2016 was the woman identified as Anna Iberti (1922–1997).
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] After the playing of the National Anthem *Il Canto degli Italiani*, the Frecce Tricolori cross the skies of Rome.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] It is tradition, for the members of the Italian government and for the presidents of the two chambers of parliament, to have pinned on their jacket, during the whole ceremony, an Italian tricolor cockade.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Following the anthem, the military parade begins, which the ground columns of military personnel saluting the President with eyes left or right with their colours dipped as they march past the dais.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Mobile column crew contingent colour guards perform the salute in a like manner.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The military parade also includes some military delegations from the United Nations, NATO, the European Union and representatives of multinational departments with an Italian component.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] On the holiday, at the Quirinale Palace, the Changing of the Guard with the Corazzieri Regiment and the Fanfare of the Carabinieri Cavalry Regiment in high uniform is carried out in solemn form.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] This solemn rite is only performed on two other occasions, during the celebrations of the Tricolour Day (7 January) and the National Unity and Armed Forces Day (4 November).
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Official ceremonies are held throughout the national territory.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Among them are the traditional receptions organized by each prefecture for the local authorities, which are preceded by solemn public demonstrations with reduced military parades that have been reviewed by the prefect in his capacity as the highest governmental authority in the province.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Similar ceremonies are also organized by the Regions and Municipalities.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] All over the world, Italian embassies organize ceremonies to which the Heads of State of the host country are invited.
[src:alps/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Greetings from the other Heads of State reach the President of Italy from all over the world.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] The **1948 Winter Olympics**, officially known as the **V Olympic Winter Games** (German: *V.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Olympische Winterspiele*; French: *Ves Jeux olympiques d'hiver*; Italian: *V Giochi olimpici invernali*; Romansh: *V Gieus olimpics d'enviern*) and commonly known as **St.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Moritz 1948** (French: *Saint-Moritz 1948*; Romansh: *San Murezzan 1948*), were a winter multi-sport event held from 30 January to 8 February 1948 in St.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] The Games were the first to be celebrated after World War II; it had been twelve years since the last Winter Games in 1936.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] It was the first Winter Olympics held during the Cold War.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] From the selection of a host city in a neutral country to the exclusion of Japan and Germany, the political atmosphere of the post-war world was inescapable during the 1948 Games.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] The organizing committee faced several challenges due to the lack of financial and human resources consumed by the war.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] These were the first of two winter Olympic Games under the IOC presidency of Sigfrid Edström.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] 28 nations marched in the opening ceremonies on 30 January 1948.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Bibi Torriani played for the Switzerland men's national ice hockey team and became the first ice hockey player to recite the Olympic Oath on behalf of all athletes.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Nearly 670 athletes competed in 22 events in four sports.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] The 1948 Games also featured two demonstration sports: military patrol, which later became the biathlon, and winter pentathlon, which was discontinued after these Games.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Notable performances were turned in by figure skaters Dick Button and Barbara Ann Scott and skier Henri Oreiller.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Most athletic venues have existed since St.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Moritz first hosted the Winter Games in 1928.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] All the venues were outdoors, meaning the Games were heavily dependent on favorable weather conditions.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Moritz to host the 1948 Games by acclamation at the 39th general session in Lausanne, Switzerland, on 6 September 1946.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] The selection process consisted of two bids, and saw St.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Moritz be selected ahead of Lake Placid, New York, United States.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Moritz was chosen because all of the venues of the 1928 Winter Olympics were available, and the Swiss resort could organize the Games much quicker than any other city except for 1936 host Garmisch-Partenkirchen which was not considered.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Despite the existence of many of the 1928 sites, it was still a difficult task to organize a Winter Olympic Games in less than 18 months.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] The Comité Olympique (CO) was composed of local dignitaries and members of the Swiss National Olympic Committee (COS).
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] They decided to separate into several sub-committees responsible for various aspects of the Games.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] These committees included housing and maintenance, venue construction, finances, and media and advertising.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] The local committees worked very closely with the Swiss federal government and the IOC to ensure that the organization of the Games proceeded without hindrance.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Since no athletes' village existed from the previous Games, the athletes and officials were housed in hotels around the city.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] It was essential for the committees to draw upon their experiences from the 1928 Olympics.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Their selection of locations for the various events was contingent on the weather conditions, as all the events were held outdoors.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Over 800 people were involved in reporting the news of the Games to the world.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Nearly 500 press credentials were issued by the Press Commission for the Games.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Television would not make its Olympic debut until 1956.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] The coverage of the 1948 Games was split between newspapers and radio broadcasts.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] The organizing committee had to provide technology, such as long-distance telephone lines and telegraph services, to assist the press in communicating with their constituents.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Over 2,200 people were needed to provide all the services for the press, officials, and athletes at the Games.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] These services included sanitation, security, and care of the venues.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Accommodating the influx of people into St.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Moritz was difficult for the organizing committee.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] It was complicated by the mountainous region in which the community was situated.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] A massive project to improve the village's transportation infrastructure had to be completed before the Games.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] This included building and widening roads for vehicular traffic.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Several train stations were built to accommodate the increased demands for public transit.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] They also had to increase the capacity of the city's sewers.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] All of the projects had to be approved by the Swiss government and justified by its impact on the success of the Games.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] To aid the organizing committee, the IOC demanded that all participating nations provide lists of their athletes several months before the Games.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Consequently, the Swiss knew exactly how many athletes and officials to plan for.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Since these Games were the first since World War II, they were named "The Games of Renewal".
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Japan and Germany were not invited to these Games because the international community still ostracized them for their role in World War II.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Their absence was short-lived, though, as they returned to Olympic competition in 1952.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] The Soviet Union did not send athletes to the St.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Moritz Games of 1948, but they did send ten delegates as observers of the Games to determine how successful the Soviet athletes would have been had they competed.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Sapporo, Japan had been the choice for the 1940 Winter Games.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] In 1938, the Japanese decided to decline the invitation to host the Games claiming that preparations for the Olympic Games were draining the country's resources.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] The IOC turned to the host of the 1936 Games, Garmisch-Partenkirchen, which would make it the only city to host consecutive Games.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] This became impractical when Germany invaded Poland on 1 September 1939; subsequently Germany withdrew its bid to host the Games.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Finland believed it could host the Games and extended an invitation to the IOC, but the Soviet Union's invasion of Finland ended all hope of an Olympic Games in 1940.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] The 1944 Winter Olympics had been awarded to Cortina d'Ampezzo, Italy in 1939.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] As the war continued, this proved impractical, and the second consecutive olympiad passed without celebrating the Games.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] The IOC was presented with two possible host cities for the first post-war Games: Lake Placid, United States and St.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] The IOC decided to award the Games to Switzerland, a neutral country immediately following World War II, to avoid political posturing by former combatants.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] The impact of World War II was still being felt in 1948.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] The lack of financial resources and human energy made the organization of the Games challenging.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Athletes were also affected by a lack of resources.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Many competitors arrived with little or no equipment.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] In one notable case, Norwegian skiers had to borrow skis from the American team to compete.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Medals were awarded in 22 events contested in 4 sports (9 disciplines).
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] There were also two demonstration sports, military patrol and the winter pentathlon.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Two sliding sports were contested at the 1948 Winter Games; the first was bobsled.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] A controversy erupted when it was alleged that the sleds of the United States team had been sabotaged.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] It was discovered that the steering wheels had been damaged.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] After news broke of the apparent improprieties a truck driver stepped forward and admitted to having accidentally backed into the shed housing the bobsleds.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] The accident, however, did not hinder the United States teams, who won a bronze in the two-man event and a gold and a bronze in the four-man event.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] The Swiss two-man teams placed first and second, which is the best possible result for the event since only two teams were allowed to enter.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] The driver of the first place team, Felix Endrich, beat his coach, the driver of the second place team, Fritz Feierabend.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] The ice hockey tournament was won by Canada, with Czechoslovakia second and Switzerland third.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] This was the fifth Olympic gold medal for Canada in hockey.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] The only team to beat Canada since hockey was introduced at the 1920 Summer Olympics was Great Britain at the 1936 Winter Olympics.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] The tournament was almost canceled when rival teams representing the United States arrived.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] An Amateur Athletic Union (AAU) team was supported by the United States Olympic Committee (USOC), and an Amateur Hockey Association (AHA) team was supported by the Ligue Internationale de Hockey sur Glace (LIHG).
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] The International Olympic Committee ruled that neither team could compete.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Still, the Swiss organizing committee allowed the AAU team to march in the opening ceremony and the AHA team to play unofficially without being eligible for medals.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Barbara Ann Scott became the first and only Canadian woman to win an Olympic gold medal in figure skating when she won the competition at St.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Despite the distraction caused by a low-flying airplane during her compulsory routine, she could muster the focus to place first entering the free skate.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] The ice had been shredded the night before the free skate by two ice hockey games (the ice resurfacer had not yet been invented); nonetheless, she was able to adjust her routine to avoid the potholes and emerge victorious.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Eighteen-year-old American Dick Button completed the unprecedented North American sweep of the figure skating gold medals.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] He led the field after the compulsory skate and won the gold medal by becoming the first person to complete a double Axel in competition.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Later in the 1952 Olympics, Dick Button would win gold a second time.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Swiss world champion Hans Gerschwiler fell during the free skate, but rebounded to win the silver medal.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] The speed skating competition was held on the same rink that had hosted the events in 1928.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] At 1,856 m (6,089 ft) above sea level, the speed skating competition was held at the second-highest altitude in Olympic history; only Squaw Valley in 1960 was higher.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] The competition was dominated by the Scandinavian countries of Norway and Sweden who won nine out of the twelve possible medals.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Scandinavians had done poorly in speed skating events up until the 1948 Games.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Their success was because speed skating in Europe had reached a standstill during World War II.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Only countries that were ancillary to the conflict had the resources to keep their speed skating programs intact.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] The 500 meter race was won by Finn Helgesen of Norway.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] There was a three-way tie for second place between Norwegian Thomas Byberg and Americans Robert Fitzgerald and Kenneth Bartholomew.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] All three had finished in exactly 43.2 seconds.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Swede Åke Seyffarth won a gold medal in the 10,000 meter race and a silver medal in the 1,500 meter race.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] The 5,000 meter event was affected by weather.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] The twenty racers encountered wind, sun, and snow during the day's competition.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Finally, long-distance specialist Reidar Liaklev from Norway prevailed.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Alpine skiing made its Olympic debut at these Games.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] A few events had been held at the 1936 Games, but the St.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Moritz Games featured a full slate of three men's and three women's alpine events.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Frenchman Henri Oreiller won a medal in all three Alpine events: gold in the downhill and combined, and bronze in the slalom.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] He was one of only two athletes to win two gold medals at the 1948 Games, and he was also the only athlete to win three or more medals.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Austria dominated the women's alpine events, winning five out of nine possible medals.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Trude Beiser was a double-medal winner, earning gold in the combined event and silver in the downhill.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] She was not the only female skier to win two medals, though United States skier Gretchen Fraser won gold in the slalom and took silver behind Beiser in the combined.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Austrian Erika Mahringer earned two medals by winning bronze medals in both the slalom and the combined.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] In cross-country skiing, 106 skiers from 15 nations competed in three events.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] The events were the 50 kilometer race, the 18 kilometer race, and the 4 x 10 kilometer relay.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] There were no women's events at the 1948 Games.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Martin Lundström of Sweden was the other athlete to win two gold medals when he won the 18 kilometer race and participated on the winning cross-country relay team.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Sweden won seven out of fifteen possible medals in the Nordic events, including all three gold medals and a sweep of the 18 kilometer race.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] All fifteen medals were won by either Sweden, Norway, or Finland.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Skeleton made its second appearance at the Olympics during these Games.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Skeleton was a form of luge that had originally appeared in the St.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Moritz region at the end of the 19th century.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] American John Heaton won his second Olympic medal in the skeleton; he won his first 20 years earlier when he was 19 years old.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Italian slider Nino Bibbia won the gold medal.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] It was the first of his 231 career wins on the Cresta Boblsed track.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] One of the curves at Cesana Pariol, where the bobsled, luge, and skeleton events took place at the 2006 Winter Olympics in Turin, was named after Bibbia.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] The Nordic combined event had been contested at each Winter Olympics since 1924.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Nordic combined required athletes to first compete in the open 18 kilometer cross-country ski race alongside the other cross-country competitors.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Their times would be assigned a point value.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] The athletes would take two jumps off the ski jump hill two days later.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] The jumps would be given a point value, and the longest jump would be combined with their cross-country time to create a score.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Traditional Nordic combined power Norway was stunned at the 1948 Games when Finland's Heikki Hasu became the first non-Norwegian to win the event.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Hasu's teammate Martti Huhtala took the silver, and Sven Israelsson from Sweden won the bronze.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] The Norwegians swept the ski jumping event.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Birger Ruud had won the gold medal in the ski jumping event at both the 1932 and 1936 Winter Games.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] The twelve-year hiatus due to World War II meant that Ruud was 36 years old in 1948.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] He had retired from competition and was coaching the Norwegian team.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] However, when he arrived at the Games, he decided to come out of retirement and compete one last time.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Despite not having competed for several years, he earned a silver medal.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Norwegian Petter Hugsted won the gold and teammate Thorleif Schjelderup won the bronze.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Two demonstration sports were held at the 1948 Games.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Military patrol had been a demonstration sport at the 1924, 1928, and 1936 Winter Olympic Games.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] It entailed a combination of cross-country skiing and shooting at targets.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Eventually the competition would be renamed Biathlon and was made an official Olympic medal sport at the 1960 Games in Squaw Valley, United States.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Winter pentathlon involved five competitions: 10 kilometer cross-country ski race, shooting, downhill skiing, fencing and horseback riding.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] This was the first and last time the event was held.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Fourteen competitors took part in the event.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] The opening ceremonies were held at 10:00 am on 30 January, along with the initial hockey games and the first two runs of the two-man bobsled.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] The closing ceremonies were held at 4:00 pm on 8 February.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] All of the medals were awarded at the closing ceremonies rather than immediately after the event, as current tradition dictates.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] The Stad Olympique (Olympic Stadium) hosted the opening and closing ceremonies.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] The stadium was also used for speed skating, the figure skating competition, and the medal games for ice hockey.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Most of the ice hockey games were held at the *Suvretta* and *Kulm* stadiums in St.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Skeleton was contested on the Cresta Run track.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Olympia Bob Run was built in 1897 and modernized for the 1948 Games, while the Cresta Run was first constructed in 1885.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] The ski jump competitions were held at Olympiaschanze ski jump hill in St.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] It was built in 1927 for the 1928 Games and remained in use until 2006.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] The alpine events were held on ski-runs in and around Piz Nair.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Moritz, the same number as the previous Winter Games in 1936.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Chile, Denmark, Iceland, Korea, and Lebanon all made their Winter Olympic debut at these Games.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Germany and Japan were not invited because of their involvement in World War II.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Despite being an Axis power, Italy was allowed to send athletes after it defected to the Allies in 1943.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Estonia, Latvia, and Lithuania had been annexed by the Soviet Union in 1940 and would not compete again as independent nations until 1992.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] Argentina returned to the Winter Games after missing the 1932 and 1936 Games, and Australia and Luxembourg did not compete in 1948, even though they had participated in 1936.
[src:alps/1948-winter-olympics] These are the top ten nations that won medals at the 1948 Winter Games.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Cortina, which had originally been awarded the 1944 Winter Olympics, beat out Montreal, Colorado Springs and Lake Placid for the right to host the 1956 Games.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] The Cortina Games were unique in that many of the venues were within walking distance of each other.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] The organising committee received financial support from the Italian government for infrastructure improvements, but the rest of the costs for the Games had to be privately financed.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Consequently, the organising committee was the first to rely heavily on corporate sponsorship for funding.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Thirty-two nations—the largest number of countries participating in the Winter Olympics until then—competed in the four sports and twenty-four events.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Austrian Toni Sailer became the first person to sweep all three alpine skiing events in a single Olympics.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] The figure skating competition was held outdoors for the last time at these Games.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Logistically, the only problem encountered was a lack of snow at the alpine skiing events.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] To remedy this, the Italian army transported large amounts of snow to ensure the courses were adequately covered.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Politics did not affect the 1956 Winter Games – unlike the Summer Games in Melbourne, Victoria, Australia later in the year which many nations boycotted after the Soviet repression of the Hungarian Revolution, and the Suez War.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] The Cortina Olympics were the first Winter Olympics televised to a multi-national audience.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Cortina co-hosted the 2026 Winter Olympics with Milan, Lombardy, 70 years after the 1956 Games.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Cortina d'Ampezzo is a ski resort village situated in the Dolomite Alps in the north-eastern corner of Italy.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] In 1956, it had a population of 6,500 people.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Count Alberto Bonacossa, an accomplished alpine skier, figure skater and a member of the International Olympic Committee (IOC) since 1925, spearheaded the effort to bring the Olympic Games to Cortina d'Ampezzo.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] He persuaded the city council of Cortina to bid for the 1944 Games.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] During the 38th IOC Congress held in London in 1939, Cortina d'Ampezzo was awarded the 1944 Winter Olympics, but the Games were canceled due to the outbreak of World War II.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] In 1946 the Italian Winter Sports Federation convened in Milan and decided to support a new attempt from Cortina to host the Winter Games.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] A delegation, led by Count Bonacossa, presented Cortina's bid to host the 1952 Winter Olympics at the 40th IOC Session in Stockholm, Sweden.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] They were backed by the city's council and the Italian National Olympic Committee (CONI, *Comitato Olimpico Nazionale Italiano*).
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] A rival bid from Oslo, Norway, soundly defeated Cortina.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Count Bonacossa's and CONI prepared a third bid, this time for the 1956 Winter Games.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] The host city selection took place in Rome, during the 43rd IOC Session.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] On 28 April 1949, Cortina d'Ampezzo was selected with 75% of the votes, over bids from Montreal, Colorado Springs and Lake Placid.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Unfortunately, Bonacossa died on 30 January 1953, three years before he could witness Cortina host the Games.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] A total of 32 nations sent athletes to Cortina d'Ampezzo.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Along with the Soviet Union, Bolivia and Pahlavi Iran competed at the Winter Games for the first time, making Bolivia the first completely tropical nation to participate in a Winter Olympics.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] South Korea, Liechtenstein and Turkey returned after having missed the 1952 Winter Olympics, while Argentina, Denmark, New Zealand and Portugal did not compete at these Games, after having participated in the previous edition.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Athletes from West Germany (FRG) and East Germany (GDR) competed together as the United Team of Germany, an arrangement that would continue for the following two Olympiads.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] The 1956 Winter Olympics was organised by a committee composed of members of the Italian National Olympic Committee and the Italian government.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Observers were sent to the Oslo Games in 1952 to collect information regarding the sports programme, infrastructure, and accommodation requirements.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] The intelligence gathered there indicated that Cortina's facilities were not up to Olympic standards.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] The town did not have an ice stadium, or a speed skating rink; the alpine ski runs, ski jump and bobsleigh run were in poor condition.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Cortina was a small village, and its infrastructure would be overwhelmed by the crowds expected for the Games.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] To accommodate the influx of people, new roads and rail lines had to be built, and the city's power grid and telephone lines expanded.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Enhancements also had to be made to sewer and water capacity.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] The Italian government supplied Italian lira 460 million for infrastructure improvements.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] The Italian Olympic Committee was responsible for funding the rest of the costs of hosting the Games.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] They did this by setting aside monies from their own budget, ticket sales, and even culling funds from local football betting pools.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] The organising committee also took the unprecedented step of selling corporate sponsorship.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] For example, Fiat was designated the official car of the 1956 Winter Olympics, and Olivetti supplied typewriters for the 400 journalists attending the Games.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] The Cold War began after the allied victory in World War II.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Until 1952, many of the Communist countries of Eastern Europe had participated in Worker's Olympics or Spartakiads.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] The Soviet Union emerged from international isolation by eschewing the Spartakiad and participating in the 1952 Summer Olympics in Helsinki; they made their Winter Olympics debut at the Cortina Games.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] The Soviets' participation at the Olympics raised the level of competition as they won the most medals and more gold medals than any other nation.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Soviet Olympic team was also notorious for skirting the edge of amateur rules.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] All Soviet athletes held some nominal jobs, but were in fact state-sponsored and trained full-time.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] According to many experts, that gave the Soviet Union a huge advantage over the United States and other Western countries, whose athletes were students or real amateurs.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] The Cortina Games were held before the Hungarian Revolution and subsequent Soviet invasion, and the Suez War, which occurred in the autumn of 1956; the Winter Games escaped the boycotts that plagued the Melbourne Olympics, which were celebrated in November and December of that year.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] The Cortina Games were the first Winter Olympics to be broadcast to a multi-national audience.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Television as a mass communication technology was expanding rapidly in the 1950s.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] In the midst of the Cold War, Europe was a propaganda battlefield as countries relayed television signals across the Iron Curtain.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Most West Germans watched the 1956 Winter Olympics via Eurovision broadcasts which were relayed all over western Europe including all major West German stations (Eurovision connectivity in 1956) The political ramifications were not the only impact television had on these Olympics.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] The Cortina Games did not generate revenue from television – the 1960 Winter Olympics in Squaw Valley were the first to do so – but were an experiment in the feasibility of televising a large multi-sport event.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] For the first time at an Olympic Games, the venues were built with television in mind.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] For example, the grand stand at the cross-country ski venue (*Lo Stadio della neve*) was built facing south so that the television cameras would not be adversely affected by the rising or setting sun.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Medals were awarded in 24 events contested in 4 sports (8 disciplines).
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] The programme for the 1956 Winter Games saw two new events added to the four sports and twenty-two events from the 1952 Olympics, namely the men's 30 kilometre cross-country ski race and the women's 3x5 kilometre cross-country relay race.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] The opening ceremonies took place on Thursday, 26 January 1956 in the Olympic Ice Stadium.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Temporary seating was added to boost the stadium's capacity to 14,000 people.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Athletes representing 32 nations marched in the ceremony and Mr Giovanni Gronchi, President of the Italian Republic, declared the Games open.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] At this point, speed skater Guido Caroli skated into the stadium with the Olympic flame.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] While he was entered on a circuit of the Ice Stadium he tripped and fell over a television cable; he regained his feet and lit the cauldron.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] The Olympic oath was delivered by Giuliana Chenal-Minuzzo; this was the first time a female athlete gave the oath at an Olympic Games.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Michał Spisak's Olympic Hymn, officially recognised as such at the IOC congress in Paris on 13 June 1955 (declined in 1958 in favor of the Olympic Hymn by Spyridon Samaras), was played for the first time at the Cortina Games.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] There were two bobsleigh events, the two-man and four-man competitions.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Every participating nation was limited to two sleighs in each event.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] The sleighs made four runs, with the total time summed.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] The Italians won gold and silver in the two-man event.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Switzerland took third place when they passed Spain on the fourth run.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] In the four-man event held a week later, the Swiss won the gold medal, Italy picked up the silver, and the United States won the bronze.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Italy had participated in all six previous Olympic bobsleigh competitions but had never reached the podium.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Italians Renzo Alverà and Eugenio Monti won the silver in the two-man competition and were also on the silver-winning four-man sleigh.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Monti's silver medals at the 1956 Games were the first of six Olympic medals he would win in his bobsleigh career.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] The bobsleigh run at Cortina was eventually renamed the Eugenio Monti track to honour his bobsleigh career.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] The medals won in bobsleigh would be the host nation's only medals at these Games.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] One complaint of the bobsleigh events was that the track surface suffered extensive damage due to overuse.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] This hampered the performance of teams drawn late in the competition.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] The eighth Olympic ice hockey tournament also served as both the European and World Championships.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Split into three pools before the tournament, the ten participating nations began by playing each team in their pool in a round robin format.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] The top two teams from each pool advanced to the final round, with the remaining teams played in a consolation group for 7th through 10th places.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Canada, Czechoslovakia, and the Soviet Union took first place in their preliminary pools with undefeated records.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Germany, the United States, and Sweden took second place in their pools.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] An important early matchup of the final round was the game between Canada and the United States.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] The Canadians had never lost to the US in Olympic play prior to that game.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] In what was considered a tremendous upset, the United States defeated Canada 4–1.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] The Americans, who placed fourth at the 1955 World Ice Hockey Championships and were not expected to medal, then faced the USSR, who won the tournament in 1954 and took silver in 1955 behind Canada, in a game that would eventually make the difference in the gold medal.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] The Russian team was leading only 1–0 late into the third period but then scored three in quick succession, overwhelming the underdogs and winning the match 4–0.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] The USSR then played Canada, who still had a chance to win the gold if they defeated the Soviets, and won 2–0 despite being dramatically outshot in the first and second periods.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] The USSR won gold, the United States surprisingly took silver and Canada, with their two losses, earned bronze, their worst result to date in Olympic play.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] The Cortina Games were the last Olympics to feature figure skating outdoors.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Skaters from the United States won five medals, sweeping the men's event and taking the top two spots in the ladies' event.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Tenley Albright was the women's Olympic champion despite sustaining a serious injury in practice.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Less than two weeks before the Olympics she was practicing her skating routine when she hit a rut in the ice and fell.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Her skate cut through several layers of clothing, and sliced her right leg at the ankle.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Her teammate Carol Heiss won the silver, and Austrian Ingrid Wendl earned the bronze medal.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Americans Hayes Jenkins, Ronald Robertson, and Jenkins' brother David Jenkins were the men's medallists.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] The Austrian pair of Sissy Schwarz and Kurt Oppelt took the gold medal in the pairs event.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Canadians Frances Dafoe and Norris Bowden won the silver and the Hungarian siblings Marianna Nagy and László Nagy defended their bronze medal from the 1952 Games.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] The Soviet Union dominated the speed skating events by winning seven of the twelve medals, including four golds.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Soviet skaters set two world records, an Olympic record, and had at least one medallist in each of the four events.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Yevgeny Grishin was the top individual performer, with two gold medals and two world records.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Grishin and Soviet teammate Yuri Mikhaylov tied in the 1,500 metre race.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] It was decided to award both of the athletes gold medals and leave the silver medal position vacant.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Sigvard Ericsson of Sweden earned gold and silver medals and set an Olympic record in the 10,000 metre event.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Six alpine skiing events were held, three for men and three for women.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] The races were the downhill, slalom and giant slalom.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Toni Sailer of Austria swept the men's gold medals, becoming the first person to win three alpine skiing golds in a single Olympics.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Led by Sailer, the Austrians dominated the alpine skiing events for both men and women, winning nine out of a possible eighteen medals.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] The Austrians were particularly successful in the giant slalom; the men swept the medals and the women took silver and bronze.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Chiharu Igaya won the first Winter Olympics medal for Japan when he placed second in the slalom.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Swiss teammates, Madeleine Berthod and Renée Colliard won the women's downhill and slalom races.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Germany earned its only gold medal of the Games when Ossi Reichert took first in the giant slalom.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Two women's events were added to the cross-country skiing programme for the first time.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] The Soviet women took the top two spots in the individual 10 kilometre race but lost to Finland in the new 3x5 kilometre relay.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] The men had a new event as well, the 30 kilometre race, which was won by Veikko Hakulinen from Finland.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] The other three men's events were won by three different nations: Norway took the 15 kilometre race, Sweden the 50 kilometre event, and the Soviet Union won the relay.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Overall the Soviet Union won seven out of a possible eighteen medals in cross-country skiing.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Sweden, behind the strong skiing of Sixten Jernberg, won six medals.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Jernberg won a gold, two silvers, and a bronze, which were the first of nine Olympic medals he would earn in his cross-country career.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] There were significant changes to the Nordic combined event at the 1956 Games.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] The event had always been a cross-country race followed by a ski jump.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Originally the competitors in the Nordic combined were entered into the open 18 kilometre cross-country race, which meant that they competed alongside athletes who were dedicated cross-country skiers.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Their times were combined with their score from two ski jumps to determine the winner.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] At the Cortina Games, the format was altered to allow the Nordic combined athletes to compete in a dedicated 15 kilometre cross-country race.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Two days later they had three jumps on the ski jump hill.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Their best two scores were combined with their cross-country time to determine a winner.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] This format would become the standard for Nordic combined competitions going forward.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Norway continued its dominance of Nordic combined when Sverre Stenersen won the gold medal.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Since its inception at the 1924 Games, the country had only lost the Nordic combined event once.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Stenersen was followed by Bengt Eriksson of Sweden and Poland's Franciszek Gąsienica Groń.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] In the ski jumping event, the Swiss jumper, Andreas Däscher introduced a new style of jumping, which would soon come to be known as the Däscher technique.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Before these Games, the athletes would hold their arms forward over their heads.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Däscher reasoned that if the athlete held his arms at his side he would fly farther.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Adherents to this new style dominated the competition.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Finnish jumpers Antti Hyvärinen and Aulis Källakorpi took first and second place; Harry Glass of Germany won the bronze medal.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] This competition marked the end of Norwegian dominance in the sport.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Since the first winter Games in 1924, the Norwegians had won the gold medal at each Olympics until 1956.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] The poor performance of the Norwegian jumpers was attributed to their refusal to use the new jumping technique.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] The closing ceremonies took place on Sunday, 5 February in the Olympic Ice Stadium.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] They were preceded by a figure skating exhibition performed by the men's, women's, and pairs figure skating champions.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] The flag bearers of each nation then entered the stadium followed by the flags of Greece, Italy, and the United States.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] These three flags were raised to honor the nation that founded the Olympics, the host nation, and the next country to host the Winter Games.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Avery Brundage, President of the International Olympic Committee, declared the Olympics closed, and a fireworks display concluded the Games.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] The opening ceremony was held on 26 January, along with the first games of the hockey tournament.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] From 27 January until 5 February, the day of the closing ceremony, at least one event final was held each day.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] † The numeral indicates the number of event finals for each sport held that day.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] A unique feature of the Cortina Olympics was the proximity of many event locations which were in walking distance of each other within the town of Cortina.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] The speed skating events were held at Lake Misurina, roughly 13 km (8.1 mi) from Cortina.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] The venues featured grandstands heated by silica coils built into the seats.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Silica coil heating was a technology that had only recently become economical.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] The competitions were held without incident except for the skiing events, which suffered from a lack of snow.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] A notable venue not found at the 1956 Games was an Olympic Village, where the athletes would be housed.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] The town of Cortina d'Ampezzo had a population of less than 7,000 people in 1956.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Local hotels were concerned that after the Olympics an Olympic Village would so significantly increase the hotel capacity it would put many of them out of business.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Athletes were billeted by local families or stayed in hotels during the Games.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] The Olympic Ice Stadium (*Stadio Olimpico Del Ghiaccio*) was intended to be the focal point of the Games.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] It was built on the banks of the Boite river just north of Cortina.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] After new roads and a bridge had been constructed, the stadium was an eight-minute walk from the center of town.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] The stadium was built to accommodate 6,000–7,000 people.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Due to space limitations the grandstands were constructed vertically, with tiers built directly on top of each other.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] There were two artificial ice rinks of 30 by 60 m (98 by 197 ft), with a total ice surface of 4,320 m2 (46,500 sq ft).
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] A special cooling plant was built under the stadium, which froze the ice through the evaporation of ammonia.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] The construction cost totaled ITL 1.3 billion (US$2.1 million in 1956), making it the most expensive venue of these Games.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] The stadium was used for the opening and closing ceremonies, all of the figure skating competitions and main ice hockey games.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] After the Games, the organising committee made the Ice Stadium a gift to the city of Cortina and turned it on a permanent installation.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] It was used as an ice skating rink in the winter and an outdoor gymnasium for judo and gymnastics in the summer and hosted the curling events at the 2026 Winter Olympics and 2026 Winter Paralympics.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] The *Apollonio Stadium* was used for select games of the ice hockey tournament.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Considerable work had to be done to bring the stadium up to date.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] A second rink was added to allow for two games to be held simultaneously.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] The stadium was outfitted with electric lights and the seating capacity was enlarged to accommodate 2,000 people.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] The bobsleigh run (*Pista Olimpica di Bob – Eugenio Monti*), was originally constructed in 1928.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] The track was rebuilt and expanded several times during the years leading up to the Olympics.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] A state-of-the-art signal board was installed displaying a diagram of the run with the position of each sleigh on the run shown with lights.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Despite being closed in 2008, the track was replaced and hosted the bobsleigh, the skeleton, and the luge during the 2026 Winter Olympics.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Situated around 2.5 km (2 mi) from Cortina, near Zuel, the "Italia" Jump (*Trampolino Olimpico Italia*) was originally built in 1923 as the "Franchetti" Jump.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] After modifications in 1926, the first structure was demolished in 1939 and rebuilt in 1940.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] With the 1956 Games coming to Cortina, the jump had to be updated again to comply with the technical demands of the Olympics.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] On 15 April 1955, the "Franchetti" Jump was finally demolished and the new "Italia Jump" was completed in the same year at a cost of nearly ITL 310 million ($500,000).
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] The reinforced concrete platform was 54 m (177 ft) high, and possessed an 87.5 m (287 ft) long, 35° steep in-run.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Two grandstands, each with a capacity for 3,000 people, were placed on either side of the landing slope; a natural amphitheatre at the bottom of the hill could hold up to 40,000 standing spectators.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] A special road was built between Cortina and the venue for the transport of athletes, officials and authorities.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] The Snow Stadium (*Stadio della neve*) was constructed 2 km (1.2 mi) from Cortina, and hosted all of the cross-country events.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Two grandstands were constructed to accommodate 6,000 people.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Three types of cross-country courses were constructed: one of 15 km (9 mi), three of 5 km (3 mi), and four of 10 km (6 mi).
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Some of these courses went through the bobsleigh run.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] As a result, a bridge had to be constructed so events occurring in the two venues would not interfere with each other.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] The alpine runs (*Le piste alpine*) were built on the slopes of Monte Tofana and Monte Faloria in the nearby Dolomite alps.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] The men's and women's downhill and slalom races were held on Tofana.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Faloria was the site of the two giant slalom events.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] It took nearly two years to complete construction of the runs.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] In previous years, lack of snow was never an issue, but in the winter of 1956 there was insufficient snowfall for skiers to safely navigate the runs.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] As a consequence, snow had to be transported from other parts of the mountains by the Italian army.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] The Misurina rink (*La pista di Misurina*) was the location of the speed skating events.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] This was the last time that speed skating at the Olympics was held on natural ice.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] The rink was established at the northern end of the lake with a mountain backdrop.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Stands were constructed to accommodate 8,500 people.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Despite the event being held outdoors on lake ice, two world records and two Olympic records were broken during the competition.
[src:alps/1956-winter-olympics] Three of the venues for these games (the bobsleigh run, indoor arena, and ski jump) would serve as film location for the 1981 James Bond film *For Your Eyes Only*.
[src:alps/1999-galtür-avalanche] The **Galtür avalanche** occurred on 23 February 1999 in the Alpine village of Galtür, Austria.
[src:alps/1999-galtür-avalanche] At 50 m (160 ft) high and traveling at 290 km/h (180 mph), the powder avalanche overturned cars, destroyed buildings and buried 57 people.
[src:alps/1999-galtür-avalanche] By the time rescue crews managed to arrive, 31 people had died.
[src:alps/1999-galtür-avalanche] It was considered the worst Alpine avalanche in 40 years.
[src:alps/1999-galtür-avalanche] Three major weather systems originating from the Atlantic accounted for large snowfalls totaling around four meters in the area.
[src:alps/1999-galtür-avalanche] Freeze-thaw conditions created a weak layer on top of an existing snow pack; further snow was then deposited on top.
[src:alps/1999-galtür-avalanche] This, coupled with high wind speeds, created large snow drifts and caused roughly 170,000 tons of snow to be deposited.
[src:alps/1999-galtür-avalanche] Like most populated regions of the Alps, Galtür was hazard-zoned according to the perceived risk of avalanches into red, yellow, and green areas.
[src:alps/1999-galtür-avalanche] Red zones are considered highly vulnerable; no development is permitted in these areas.
[src:alps/1999-galtür-avalanche] Yellow zones pose a moderate risk; development is allowed but structures must be reinforced to resist avalanches.
[src:alps/1999-galtür-avalanche] Green zones are considered avalanche-safe; development is permitted with no reinforcement required.
[src:alps/1999-galtür-avalanche] Galtür had been designated a green zone, and because of this, the resort was not well-prepared for an avalanche.
[src:alps/1999-galtür-avalanche] In January 1999, a series of storms occurred, bringing with them 4 m (13 ft) of fine snow forming a large snow pack on the mountains above Galtür.
[src:alps/1999-galtür-avalanche] Later that month a melt-crust developed, the upper layers melting during the day and refreezing at night.
[src:alps/1999-galtür-avalanche] The cause of the avalanches puzzled scientists for a long time: although the area was prone to avalanches, never before had they occurred on such a scale as this, reaching the village.
[src:alps/1999-galtür-avalanche] A complex sequence of events led to the event.
[src:alps/1999-galtür-avalanche] On 20 January, an Atlantic storm was forming 4,000 km (2,500 mi) away.
[src:alps/1999-galtür-avalanche] Turbulent warm air from the tropics headed north, cooled, and swung back towards Europe.
[src:alps/1999-galtür-avalanche] Combined with cold Arctic air coming from the north, there was a very dry and light type of snowfall exceeding 4 m (13 ft).
[src:alps/1999-galtür-avalanche] Therefore, a massive snow pack formed on the mountains above Galtür.
[src:alps/1999-galtür-avalanche] Northwest winds piled the snow to increasing depths.
[src:alps/1999-galtür-avalanche] At Galtür, the snow initially bonded with the underlying ice of the melt crust and it was able to stay in place for longer than usual.
[src:alps/1999-galtür-avalanche] As new snow fell, the melt-crust became unstable because of the ever increasing weight of the snow on top.
[src:alps/1999-galtür-avalanche] On 23 February at 15:59, the melt-crust failed; the resulting powder avalanche contained a central layer of which scientists were unaware.
[src:alps/1999-galtür-avalanche] Known as the saltation layer, it was primarily responsible for the destruction of buildings.
[src:alps/1999-galtür-avalanche] As the powerful powder avalanche crashed down the mountainside, it picked up more and more snow as it went.
[src:alps/1999-galtür-avalanche] There were also 120 km/h (75 mph) winds which caused the saltation layer of snow to move causing this disaster.
[src:alps/1999-galtür-avalanche] Soon after the avalanche rescuers began to look for survivors; in 24 hours the rescuers saved 26 people.
[src:alps/1999-galtür-avalanche] A rescue dog, Heiko, amply proved the value dogs have in avalanche rescue, saving many lives, as did a second dog, a Labrador-Alsatian cross named Jack, who was buried under snow for 24 hours.
[src:alps/1999-galtür-avalanche] The day after the avalanche, 31 people were confirmed dead.
[src:alps/1999-galtür-avalanche] Galtür and several neighboring communities needed supplies and evacuation.
[src:alps/1999-galtür-avalanche] Several countries contributed aircraft: to support the Austrian Bell 212, Bell 204 and Alouette III helicopters, Germany sent UH-1D and CH-53G, the German Federal Border Guard (Bundesgrenzschutz) Super Pumas, the U.S.
[src:alps/1999-galtür-avalanche] Army 10 UH-60 Black Hawks, and the Swiss and French air forces together six Super Puma/Cougar helicopters.
[src:alps/1999-galtür-avalanche] In addition to them, the Austrian Ministry of the Interior supplied six helicopters, private companies nine, and the ÖAMTC used two EC 135 rescue helicopters to transport injured patients.
[src:alps/1999-galtür-avalanche] An international group of over 50 helicopters from Austria, France, Switzerland, Germany, and the USA evacuated over 7,000 people.
[src:alps/1999-galtür-avalanche] In 935 hours of flight, 18,406 people and 271 tons of supplies were transported.
[src:alps/1999-galtür-avalanche] In order to avoid causing additional avalanches, the crews flew below the tree line.
[src:alps/1999-galtür-avalanche] The helicopters flew on the right side of the valley to separate traffic.
[src:alps/1999-galtür-avalanche] The Austrian helicopters transported the evacuated to the army barracks at Landeck, while the other air crews flew the evacuees to a section of the Inn valley highway.
[src:alps/1999-galtür-avalanche] The families of the victims demanded to know why the avalanche penetrated the supposedly safe zone and devastated Galtür.
[src:alps/1999-galtür-avalanche] However, hazard zoning is dependent on the historical record, and there was no evidence of avalanches traveling so far on this track in the past.
[src:alps/1999-galtür-avalanche] Since this disaster there have been renewed efforts to improve avalanche knowledge and forecasting so that hazard zones can be accurately predicted.
[src:alps/1999-galtür-avalanche] This is particularly important if land use or climate changes render past information less useful.
[src:alps/1999-galtür-avalanche] The response has included the extension of the hazard zones, with steel fences constructed on all mountainsides above the village to break up the areas where unstable snow packs can form, creating smaller shelves overall that reduce the size and scale of any future avalanches.
[src:alps/1999-galtür-avalanche] A 300 m (980 ft) avalanche dam directly protects the village.
[src:alps/1999-galtür-avalanche] There has been rezoning, so the former Green zone is now a higher risk zone.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The **Alps** (/ælps/) are some of the highest and most extensive mountain ranges in Europe, stretching approximately 1,200 km (750 mi) across several Alpine countries (from west to east): Monaco, France, Switzerland, Italy, Liechtenstein, Germany, Austria, and Slovenia.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The Alpine arch extends from Nice on the western Mediterranean to Trieste on the Adriatic and Vienna at the beginning of the Pannonian Basin.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The mountains were formed over tens of millions of years as the African and Eurasian tectonic plates collided.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Extreme shortening caused by the event resulted in marine sedimentary rocks rising by thrusting and folding into high mountain peaks such as Mont Blanc and the Matterhorn.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The Alpine region area contains 82 peaks higher than 4,000 m (13,000 ft).
[src:alps/alps-p01] The altitude and size of the range affect the climate in Europe; in the mountains, precipitation levels vary greatly and climatic conditions consist of distinct zones.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Evidence of human habitation in the Alps goes back to the Palaeolithic era.
[src:alps/alps-p01] A mummified man ("Ötzi"), determined to be 5,000 years old, was discovered on a glacier at the Austrian–Italian border in 1991.
[src:alps/alps-p01] By the 6th century BC, the Celtic La Tène culture was well established.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Hannibal notably crossed the Alps with a herd of elephants, and the Romans had settlements in the region.
[src:alps/alps-p01] In 1800, Napoleon crossed one of the mountain passes with an army of 40,000.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The 18th and 19th centuries saw an influx of naturalists, writers, and artists, in particular, the Romanticists, followed by the Golden Age of Alpinism as mountaineers began to ascend the peaks of the Alps.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The Alpine region has a strong cultural identity.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Traditional practices such as farming, cheese making, and woodworking still thrive in Alpine villages.
[src:alps/alps-p01] However, the tourist industry began to grow early in the 20th century and expanded significantly after World War II, eventually becoming the dominant industry by the end of the century.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The Winter Olympic Games have been hosted in the Swiss, French, Italian, Austrian and German Alps.
[src:alps/alps-p01] As of 2010, the region is home to 14 million people and has 120 million annual visitors.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The English word *Alps* comes from the Latin *Alpes*.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The Latin word *Alpes* could possibly come from the adjective *albus* ("white"), or could possibly come from the Greek goddess Alphito, whose name is related to *alphita*, the "white flour"; *alphos*, a dull white leprosy; and finally the Proto-Indo-European word *albʰós.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Similarly, the river god Alpheus is also supposed to derive from the Greek *alphos* and means whitish.
[src:alps/alps-p01] In his commentary on the *Aeneid* of Virgil, the late fourth-century grammarian Maurus Servius Honoratus says that all high mountains are called *Alpes* by Celts.
[src:alps/alps-p01] According to the *Oxford English Dictionary*, the Latin *Alpes* might derive from a pre-Indo-European word **alb* "hill"; "Albania" is a related derivation.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Albania, the name of the region known as the country of Albania, has been used as a name for several mountainous areas across Europe.
[src:alps/alps-p01] In Roman times, "Albania" was a name for the eastern Caucasus, while in the English languages "Albania" (or "Albany") was occasionally used as a name for Scotland, although it is more likely derived from the Latin word *albus*, the colour white.
[src:alps/alps-p01] In modern languages the term *alp*, *alm*, *albe* or *alpe* refers to grazing pastures in the alpine regions below the glaciers, not the peaks.
[src:alps/alps-p01] An *alp* refers to a high mountain pasture, typically near or above the tree line, where cows and other livestock are taken to be grazed during the summer months and where huts and hay barns can be found, sometimes constituting tiny hamlets.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Therefore, the term "the Alps", as a reference to the mountains, is a misnomer.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The Alps are a crescent shaped geographic feature of central Europe that ranges in an 800 km (500 mi) arc (curved line) from east to west and is 200 km (120 mi) in width.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The mean height of the mountain peaks is 2.5 km (1.6 mi).
[src:alps/alps-p01] The range stretches from the Mediterranean Sea north above the Po basin, extending through France from Grenoble, and stretching eastward through mid and southern Switzerland.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The range continues onward toward Vienna, Austria, and southeast to the Adriatic Sea and Slovenia.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Depending on the definitions used, the Alpokalja foothills in western Hungary may also qualify as part of the Alps.
[src:alps/alps-p01] To the south it dips into northern Italy and to the north extends to the southern border of Bavaria in Germany.
[src:alps/alps-p01] In areas like Chiasso, Switzerland, and Allgäu, Bavaria, the demarcation between the mountain range and the flatlands is clear; in other places such as Geneva, it is less clear.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The highest portion of the range is divided by the glacial trough of the Rhône valley, from Mont Blanc to the Matterhorn and Monte Rosa on the southern side, and the Bernese Alps on the northern.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The peaks in the easterly portion of the range, in Austria and Slovenia, are smaller than those in the central and western portions.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The highest peaks of the Western Alps and Eastern Alps, respectively, are Mont Blanc, at 4,810 m (15,780 ft), and Piz Bernina, at 4,049 m (13,284 ft).
[src:alps/alps-p01] The second-highest major peaks are the Dufourspitze of the Monte Rosa massif, at 4,634 m (15,203 ft), and Ortler, at 3,905 m (12,810 ft), respectively.
[src:alps/alps-p01] A series of lower mountain ranges run parallel to the main chain of the Alps, including the French Prealps in France and the Jura Mountains in Switzerland and France.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The secondary chain of the Alps follows the watershed from the Mediterranean Sea to the Wienerwald, passing over many of the highest and most well-known peaks in the Alps.
[src:alps/alps-p01] From the Colle di Cadibona to Col de Tende it runs westwards, before turning to the northwest and then, near the Colle della Maddalena, to the north.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Upon reaching the Swiss border, the line of the main chain heads approximately east-northeast, a heading it follows until its end near Vienna.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The northeast end of the Alpine arc, directly on the Danube, which flows into the Black Sea, is the Leopoldsberg near Vienna.
[src:alps/alps-p01] In contrast, the southeastern part of the Alps ends on the Adriatic Sea in the area around Trieste towards Duino and Barcola.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Crossing routes by foot, road, or train are known as *passes*, and usually consist of depressions in the mountains in which a valley leads from the plains and hilly pre-mountainous zones.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The Alps have been crossed for explorations, commerce (historical: salt, wine, grain, textiles, and metals), military purposes, political reasons, religious and cultural motivations, and migrations for thousands of years.
[src:alps/alps-p01] For a thousands of years these routes had been footpaths only.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Many had been used by explorers of pre-civilised cultures at least since Stone Ages.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The oldest known human mummy, the Ötzi, has been found 1991 on the Tisenjoch on the Austrian-Italian border; he has been killed there about 5300 years ago.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The Romans built several Roman Roads over several mountain passes in the Alps in order to control Roman territory west, north, north-east of their home base.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Usually, they were also used by animal drawn carts.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Merchant traffic was supported by pack animals such as mules, horses, and even elephants (c.f.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Already during the Roman Empire, but again in the late Middle Ages heavy carts and sleighs were in use on drivable roads over Alpine passes.
[src:alps/alps-p01] In the medieval period, hospices were established by religious orders at the summits of many of the main passes.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Nowadays, the most important passes are the Col de l'Iseran (the highest), the Col Agnel, the Brenner Pass, the Mont Cenis Pass, the Great St.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Bernard Pass, the Col de Tende, the Saint Gotthard Pass, the Semmering Pass, the Simplon Pass, and the Stelvio Pass.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Crossing the Italian-Austrian border, the Brenner Pass separates the Ötztal Alps and Zillertal Alps and has been in use as a regular trading route since the Roman Times, and again since 14th century.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The lowest of the Alpine passes at 984 m (3,228 ft) is the Semmering Pass crossing from Lower Austria to Styria.
[src:alps/alps-p01] It has been in continuous use as a trade route since the 12th century, instead of the Roman Road over the Wechsel Pass.
[src:alps/alps-p01] A railroad with a tunnel 1.434 km (0.891 mi) long was built along the route of the pass in the mid-19th century.
[src:alps/alps-p01] With a summit of 2,469 m (8,100 ft), the Great St Bernard Pass is one of the highest in the Alps, crossing the Italian-Swiss border east of the Pennine Alps along the flanks of Mont Blanc.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The pass was already used by the Romans to control north-western provinces, and later by Napoleon Bonaparte to cross 40,000 troops in 1800.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The Mont Cenis pass has been a major commercial and military road between Western Europe and Italy.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The pass was crossed by many troops on their way to the Italian peninsula.
[src:alps/alps-p01] From Constantine I, Pepin the Short and Charlemagne to Henry IV, Napoléon and more recently the German Gebirgsjägers during World War II.
[src:alps/alps-p01] In the 19th century, the principal passes of the Alps were modernised by engineers to speed up passenger and freight transport.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The Mont Cenis Pass has been supplanted by the Fréjus Rail Tunnel opening in 1871, while the Fréjus Road Tunnel opened 1980.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Railway lines could not be built in the Alps without tunnels and bridges.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Apart from the Mont Cenis Railway Tunnel the Semmering Railway Tunnel and the St Gotthard Railway Tunnel were built between 1872 and 1882.
[src:alps/alps-p01] By the early 20th century eight trans-alpine railway lines had been put into operation.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The Saint Gotthard Pass crosses from Central Switzerland to Ticino.
[src:alps/alps-p01] In 1882 the 15 km-long (9.3 mi) Saint Gotthard Railway Tunnel was opened connecting Lucerne in Switzerland, with Milan in Italy.
[src:alps/alps-p01] 98 years later followed the Gotthard Road Tunnel (16.9 km (10.5 mi) long) connecting the A2 motorway in Göschenen on the north side with Airolo on the south side, exactly like the railway tunnel.
[src:alps/alps-p01] On 1 June 2016 the world's longest railway tunnel, the Gotthard Base Tunnel, was opened, which connects Erstfeld in canton of Uri with Bodio in canton of Ticino by two single tubes of 57.1 km (35.5 mi).
[src:alps/alps-p01] It is the first tunnel that traverses the Alps on a flat route.
[src:alps/alps-p01] From 11 December 2016, it has been part of the regular railway timetable and used hourly as standard ride between Basel/Lucerne/Zurich and Bellinzona/Lugano/Milan.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The highest drivable pass in the alps is the Col de l'Iseran in Savoy (France) at 2,770 m (9,088 ft), followed by the Stelvio Pass in northern Italy at 2,757 m (9,045 ft); the road was built in the 1820s.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The Union Internationale des Associations d'Alpinisme (UIAA) has defined a list of 82 "official" Alpine summits that reach at least 4,000 m (13,123 ft).
[src:alps/alps-p01] The list includes not only mountains, but also subpeaks with little prominence that are considered important mountaineering objectives.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Below are listed the 29 "four-thousanders" with at least 300 m (984 ft) of prominence.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Karl Blodig (1859–1956) was among the first to successfully climb all the major 4,000 m peaks.
[src:alps/alps-p01] He completed his series of ascents in 1911.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Many of the big Alpine three-thousanders were climbed in the early 19th century, notably the Grossglockner (1800) and the Ortler (1804), although some of them were climbed only much later, such at Mont Pelvoux (1848), Monte Viso (1861) and La Meije (1877).
[src:alps/alps-p01] The first British Mont Blanc ascent by a man was in 1788; the first ascent by a woman was in 1808.
[src:alps/alps-p01] By the mid-1850s Swiss mountaineers had ascended most of the peaks and were eagerly sought as mountain guides.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Edward Whymper reached the top of the Matterhorn in 1865 (after seven attempts), and in 1938 the last of the six great north faces of the Alps was climbed with the first ascent of the Eiger *Nordwand* (north face of the Eiger).
[src:alps/alps-p01] The Alps provide lowland Europe with drinking water, irrigation, and hydroelectric power.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Although the area is only about 11% of the surface area of Europe, the Alps provide up to 90% of water to lowland Europe, particularly to arid areas and during the summer months.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Cities such as Milan depend on 80% of water from Alpine runoff.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Water from the rivers is used in at least 550 hydroelectricity power plants, considering only those producing at least 10MW of electricity.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Major European rivers flow from the Alps, such as the Rhine, the Rhône, the Ticino->Po, and the Inn->Danube, all of which have headwaters in the Alps and flow into neighbouring countries, finally emptying into the North Sea, the Mediterranean Sea, the Adriatic Sea and the Black Sea.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Other rivers such as the Danube have major tributaries flowing into them that originate in the Alps.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The Rhône is second to the Nile as a freshwater source to the Mediterranean Sea; the river begins as glacial meltwater, flows into Lake Geneva, and from there to France where one of its uses is to cool nuclear power plants.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The Rhine originates in a 30 km2 (12 sq mi) area in Switzerland and represents almost 60% of water exported from the country.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Tributary valleys, some of which are complicated, channel water to the main valleys which can experience flooding during the snowmelt season when rapid runoff causes debris torrents and swollen rivers.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The rivers flow through lakes, such as Lake Geneva, a crescent-shaped lake crossing the Swiss border with Lausanne on the Swiss side and the town of Evian-les-Bains on the French side.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Bartholomew's chapel was built on the south side of the Königssee, accessible only by boat or by climbing over the abutting peaks.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Additionally, the Alps have led to the creation of large lakes in Italy.
[src:alps/alps-p01] For instance, the Sarca, the primary inflow of Lake Garda, originates in the Italian Alps.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The Italian Lakes are a popular tourist destination since the Roman Era for their mild climate.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Scientists have been studying the impact of climate change and water use.
[src:alps/alps-p01] For example, each year more water is diverted from rivers for snowmaking in the ski resorts, the effect of which is yet unknown.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The Alps are a classic example of what happens when a temperate area at lower altitude gives way to higher-elevation terrain.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Elevations around the world that have cold climates similar to those of the polar regions have been called Alpine.
[src:alps/alps-p01] A rise from sea level into the upper regions of the atmosphere causes the temperature to decrease (see adiabatic lapse rate).
[src:alps/alps-p01] The effect of mountain chains on prevailing winds is to carry warm air belonging to the lower region into an upper zone, where it expands in volume at the cost of a proportionate loss of temperature, often accompanied by precipitation in the form of snow or rain.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The height of the Alps is sufficient to divide the weather patterns in Europe into a wet north and dry south because moisture is sucked from the air as it flows over the high peaks.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The severe weather in the Alps has been studied since the 18th century; particularly the weather patterns such as the seasonal foehn wind.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Numerous weather stations were placed in the mountains early in the early 20th century, providing continuous data for climatologists.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Some of the valleys are quite arid such as the Aosta Valley in Italy, the Maurienne in France, the Valais in Switzerland, and northern Tyrol.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The areas that are not arid and receive high precipitation experience periodic flooding from rapid snowmelt and runoff.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The mean precipitation in the Alps ranges from a low of 2,600 mm (100 in) per year to 3,600 mm (140 in) per year, with the higher levels occurring at high altitudes.
[src:alps/alps-p01] At altitudes between 1,000 and 3,000 m (3,300 and 9,800 ft), snowfall begins in November and accumulates through to April or May when the melt begins.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Snow lines vary from 2,400 to 3,000 m (7,900 to 9,800 ft), above which the snow is permanent and the temperatures hover around the freezing point even during July and August.
[src:alps/alps-p01] High-water levels in streams and rivers peak in June and July when the snow is still melting at the higher altitudes.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The Alps are split into five climatic zones, each with different vegetation.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The climate, plant life, and animal life vary among the different sections or zones of the mountains.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The lowest zone is the colline zone, which exists between 500 and 1,000 m (1,600 and 3,300 ft), depending on the location.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The Alpine zone, extending from tree line to the snow line, is followed by the glacial zone, which covers the glaciated areas of the mountain.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Climatic conditions show variances within the same zones; for example, weather conditions at the head of a mountain valley, extending directly from the peaks, are colder and more severe than those at the mouth of a valley which tend to be less severe and receive less snowfall.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Various models of climate change have been projected into the 22nd century for the Alps, with an expectation that a trend toward increased temperatures will have an effect on snowfall, snowpack, glaciation, and river runoff.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Important geological concepts were established as naturalists began studying the rock formations of the Alps in the 18th century.
[src:alps/alps-p01] In the mid-19th century, the now-defunct idea of geosynclines was used to explain the presence of "folded" mountain chains.
[src:alps/alps-p01] This theory was replaced in the mid-20th century by the theory of plate tectonics.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The formation of the Alps (the Alpine orogeny) was an episodic process that began about 300 million years ago.
[src:alps/alps-p01] In the Paleozoic Era the Pangaean supercontinent consisted of a single tectonic plate; it broke into separate plates during the Mesozoic Era and the Tethys sea developed between Laurasia and Gondwana during the Jurassic Period.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The Tethys was later squeezed between colliding plates causing the formation of mountain ranges called the Alpide belt, from Gibraltar through the Himalayas to Indonesia—a process that began at the end of the Mesozoic and continues into the present.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The formation of the Alps was a segment of this orogenic process, caused by the collision between the African and the Eurasian plates that began in the late Cretaceous Period.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Under extreme compressive stresses and pressure, marine sedimentary rocks were uplifted, forming characteristic recumbent folds, and thrust faults.
[src:alps/alps-p01] As the rising peaks underwent erosion, a layer of marine flysch sediments was deposited in the foreland basin, and the sediments became involved in younger folds as the orogeny progressed.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Coarse sediments from the continual uplift and erosion were later deposited in foreland areas north of the Alps.
[src:alps/alps-p01] These regions in Switzerland and Bavaria are well-developed, containing classic examples of flysch, which is sedimentary rock formed during mountain building.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The Alpine orogeny occurred in ongoing cycles through to the Paleogene causing differences in folded structures, with a late-stage orogeny causing the development of the Jura Mountains.
[src:alps/alps-p01] A series of tectonic events in the Triassic, Jurassic and Cretaceous periods caused different paleogeographic regions.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The Alps are subdivided by different lithology (rock composition) and nappe structures according to the orogenic events that affected them.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The geological subdivision differentiates the Western, Eastern Alps, and Southern Alps: the Helveticum in the north, the Penninicum and Austroalpine system in the centre and, south of the Periadriatic Seam, the Southern Alpine system.
[src:alps/alps-p01] According to geologist Stefan Schmid, because the Western Alps underwent a metamorphic event in the Cenozoic Era while the Austroalpine peaks underwent an event in the Cretaceous Period, the two areas show distinct differences in nappe formations.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Flysch deposits in the Southern Alps of Lombardy probably occurred in the Cretaceous or later.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Peaks in France, Italy and Switzerland lie in the "Houillière zone", which consists of basement with sediments from the Mesozoic Era.
[src:alps/alps-p01] High "massifs" with external sedimentary cover are more common in the Western Alps and were affected by Neogene Period thin-skinned thrusting whereas the Eastern Alps have comparatively few high peaked massifs.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Similarly the peaks in eastern Switzerland extending to western Austria (Helvetic nappes) consist of thin-skinned sedimentary folding that detached from former basement rock.
[src:alps/alps-p01] In simple terms, the structure of the Alps consists of layers of rock of European, African, and oceanic (Tethyan) origin.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The bottom nappe structure is of continental European origin, above which are stacked marine sediment nappes, topped off by nappes derived from the African plate.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The Matterhorn is an example of the ongoing orogeny and shows evidence of great folding.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The tip of the mountain consists of gneisses from the African plate; the base of the peak, below the glaciated area, consists of European basement rock.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The sequence of Tethyan marine sediments and their oceanic basement is sandwiched between rock derived from the African and European plates.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The core regions of the Alpine orogenic belt have been folded and fractured in such a manner that erosion produced the characteristic steep vertical peaks of the Swiss Alps that rise seemingly straight out of the foreland areas.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Peaks such as Mont Blanc, the Matterhorn, and high peaks in the Pennine Alps, the Briançonnais, and Hohe Tauern consist of layers of rock from the various orogenies including exposures of basement rock.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Due to the ever-present geologic instability, earthquakes continue in the Alps to this day.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Typically, the largest earthquakes in the alps have been between magnitude 6 and 7 on the Richter scale.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Geodetic measurements show ongoing topographic uplift at rates of up to about 2.5 mm per year in the North, Western and Central Alps, and at ~1 mm per year in the Eastern and South-Western Alps.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The Alps are a source of minerals that have been mined for thousands of years.
[src:alps/alps-p01] In the 8th to 6th centuries, BC during the Hallstatt culture, Celtic tribes mined copper; later the Romans mined gold for coins in the Bad Gastein area.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Erzberg in Styria furnishes high-quality iron ore for the steel industry.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Crystals, such as cinnabar, amethyst, and quartz, are found throughout much of the Alpine region.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The cinnabar deposits in Slovenia are a notable source of cinnabar pigments.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Alpine crystals have been studied and collected for hundreds of years and began to be classified in the 18th century.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Leonhard Euler studied the shapes of crystals, and by the 19th-century crystal hunting was common in Alpine regions.
[src:alps/alps-p01] David Friedrich Wiser amassed a collection of 8000 crystals that he studied and documented.
[src:alps/alps-p01] In the 20th century Robert Parker wrote a well-known work about the rock crystals of the Swiss Alps; at the same period a commission was established to control and standardise the naming of Alpine minerals.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Because of his work he came to be known as the "father of the ice-age concept" although other naturalists before him put forth similar ideas.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Agassiz studied glacier movement in the 1840s at the Unteraar Glacier where he found the glacier moved 100 m (328 ft) per year, more rapidly in the middle than at the edges.
[src:alps/alps-p01] His work was continued by other scientists and now a permanent laboratory exists inside a glacier under the Jungfraujoch, devoted exclusively to the study of Alpine glaciers.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Glaciers pick up rocks and sediment with them as they flow.
[src:alps/alps-p01] This causes erosion and the formation of valleys over time.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The Inn valley is an example of a valley carved by glaciers during the ice ages with a typical terraced structure caused by erosion.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Eroded rocks from the most recent ice age lie at the bottom of the valley while the top of the valley consists of erosion from earlier ice ages.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Glacial valleys have characteristically steep walls (reliefs); valleys with lower reliefs and talus slopes are remnants of glacial troughs or previously infilled valleys.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Moraines, piles of rock picked up during the movement of the glacier, accumulate at edges, centre, and the terminus of glaciers.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Alpine glaciers can be straight rivers of ice, long sweeping rivers, spread in a fan-like shape (Piedmont glaciers), and curtains of ice that hang from vertical slopes of the mountain peaks.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The stress of the movement causes the ice to break and crack loudly, perhaps explaining why the mountains were believed to be home to dragons in the medieval period.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The cracking creates unpredictable and dangerous crevasses, often invisible under new snowfall, which causes the greatest danger to mountaineers.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Glaciers end in ice caves (the Rhône Glacier), by trailing into a lake or river, or by shedding snowmelt on a meadow.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Sometimes a piece of glacier will detach or break resulting in flooding, property damage, and loss of life.
[src:alps/alps-p01] High levels of precipitation cause the glaciers to descend to permafrost levels in some areas whereas in other, more arid regions, glaciers remain above about the 3,500 m (11,483 ft) level.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The 1,817 km2 (702 sq mi) of the Alps covered by glaciers in 1876 had shrunk to 1,342 km2 (518 sq mi) by 1973, resulting in decreased river run-off levels.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Forty percent of the glaciation in Austria has disappeared since 1850, and 30% of that in Switzerland.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Although the Alpine topography shows marked glacial morphologies, the mechanisms by which glacial reshaping occurs are unclear.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Numerical modelling suggests that glacial erosion propagates from low elevations to high elevations leading to an early increase of local relief followed by lowering of the mean orogen elevation.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Thirteen thousand species of plants have been identified in the Alpine regions.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Alpine plants are grouped by habitat and soil type which can be limestone or non-calcareous.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The habitats range from meadows, bogs, and woodland (deciduous and coniferous) areas to soil-less scree and moraines, and rock faces and ridges.
[src:alps/alps-p01] A natural vegetation limit with altitude is given by the presence of the chief deciduous trees—oak, beech, ash and sycamore maple.
[src:alps/alps-p01] These do not reach the same elevation, nor are they often found growing together, but their upper limit corresponds accurately enough to the change from a temperate to a colder climate that is further proved by a change in the presence of wild herbaceous vegetation.
[src:alps/alps-p01] This limit usually lies about 1,200 m (3,900 ft) above the sea on the north side of the Alps, but on the southern slopes it often rises to 1,500 m (4,900 ft), sometimes even to 1,700 m (5,600 ft).
[src:alps/alps-p01] Above the forestry, there is often a band of dwarf pine trees (*Pinus mugo*), which is in turn superseded by *Alpenrosen*, dwarf shrubs, typically *Rhododendron ferrugineum* (on acid soils) or *Rhododendron hirsutum* (on alkaline soils).
[src:alps/alps-p01] Although Alpenrose prefers acidic soil, the plants are found throughout the region.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Above the tree line is the area defined as "alpine" where in the alpine meadow plants are found that have adapted well to harsh conditions of cold temperatures, aridity, and high altitudes.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The alpine area fluctuates greatly because of regional fluctuations in tree lines.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Alpine plants such as the Alpine gentian grow in abundance in areas such as the meadows above the Lauterbrunnental.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Gentians are named after the Illyrian king Gentius, and 40 species of the early-spring blooming flower grow in the Alps, in a range of 1,500 to 2,400 m (4,900 to 7,900 ft).
[src:alps/alps-p01] Writing about the gentians in Switzerland D.
[src:alps/alps-p01] On the highest rocky ledges, the spring flowers bloom in the summer.
[src:alps/alps-p01] At these higher altitudes, the plants tend to form isolated cushions.
[src:alps/alps-p01] In the Alps, several species of flowering plants have been recorded above 4,000 m (13,000 ft), including *Ranunculus glacialis*, *Androsace alpina* and *Saxifraga biflora*.
[src:alps/alps-p01] *Eritrichium nanum*, commonly known as the King of the Alps, is the most elusive of the alpine flowers, growing on rocky ridges at 2,600 to 3,750 m (8,530 to 12,300 ft).
[src:alps/alps-p01] Perhaps the best known of the alpine plants is Edelweiss which grows in rocky areas and can be found at altitudes as low as 1,200 m (3,900 ft) and as high as 3,400 m (11,200 ft).
[src:alps/alps-p01] The plants that grow at the highest altitudes have adapted to conditions by specialisation such as growing in rock screes that give protection from winds.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The alpine meadows are also known for their distinct floral aromas during summer: the sensory landscape is often defined by the strong, spicy-sweet fragrance of Alpine clover (*Trifolium alpinum*), a characteristic scent of the high pastures.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The extreme and stressful climatic conditions give way to the growth of plant species with secondary metabolites important for medicinal purposes.
[src:alps/alps-p01] *Origanum vulgare*, *Prunella vulgaris*, *Solanum nigrum*, and *Urtica dioica* are some of the more useful medicinal species found in the Alps.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Human interference has nearly exterminated the trees in many areas, and, except for the beech forests of the Austrian Alps, forests of deciduous trees are rarely found after the extreme deforestation between the 17th and 19th centuries.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The vegetation has changed since the second half of the 20th century, as the high alpine meadows cease to be harvested for hay or used for grazing which eventually might result in a regrowth of the forest.
[src:alps/alps-p01] In some areas, the modern practice of building ski runs by mechanical means has destroyed the underlying tundra from which the plant life cannot recover during the non-skiing months, whereas areas that still practice a natural *piste* type of ski slope building preserve the fragile underlayers.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The Alps are a habitat for 30,000 species of wildlife, ranging from the tiniest snow fleas to brown bears, many of which have made adaptations to the harsh cold conditions and high altitudes to the point that some only survive in specific micro-climates either directly above or below the snow line.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The largest mammal to live in the highest altitudes are the alpine ibex, which have been sighted as high as 3,000 m (9,800 ft).
[src:alps/alps-p01] The ibex live in caves and descend to eat the succulent alpine grasses.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Classified as antelopes, chamois are smaller than ibex and found throughout the Alps, living above the tree line and are common in the entire alpine range.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Areas of the eastern Alps are still home to brown bears.
[src:alps/alps-p01] In Switzerland the canton of Bern was named for the bears but the last bear is recorded as having been killed in 1792 above Kleine Scheidegg by three hunters from Grindelwald.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Many rodents such as voles live underground.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Marmots live almost exclusively above the tree line as high as 2,700 m (8,900 ft).
[src:alps/alps-p01] They hibernate in large groups to provide warmth, and can be found in all areas of the Alps, in large colonies they build beneath the alpine pastures.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Golden eagles and bearded vultures are the largest birds to be found in the Alps; they nest high on rocky ledges and can be found at altitudes of 2,400 m (7,900 ft).
[src:alps/alps-p01] The most common bird is the alpine chough which can be found scavenging at climber's huts or the Jungfraujoch, a high-altitude tourist destination.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Reptiles such as adders and vipers live up to the snow line; because they cannot bear the cold temperatures they hibernate underground and soak up the warmth on rocky ledges.
[src:alps/alps-p01] The high-altitude Alpine salamanders have adapted to living above the snow line by giving birth to fully developed young rather than laying eggs.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Brown trout can be found in the streams up to the snow line.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Molluscs such as the wood snail live up the snow line.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Popularly gathered as food, the snails are now protected.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Several species of moths live in the Alps, some of which are believed to have evolved in the same habitat up to 120 million years ago, long before the Alps were created.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Blue butterflies can commonly be seen drinking from the snowmelt; some species of blues fly as high as 1,800 m (5,900 ft).
[src:alps/alps-p01] The butterflies tend to be large, such as those from the swallowtail *Parnassius* family, with a habitat that ranges to 1,800 m (5,900 ft).
[src:alps/alps-p01] Twelve species of beetles have habitats up to the snow line; the most beautiful and formerly collected for its colours but now protected is *Rosalia alpina*.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Spiders, such as the large wolf spider, live above the snow line and can be seen as high as 400 m (1,300 ft).
[src:alps/alps-p01] Scorpions can be found in the Italian Alps.
[src:alps/alps-p01] Some of the species of moths and insects show evidence of having been indigenous to the area from as long ago as the Alpine orogeny.
[src:alps/alps-p01] In Émosson in Valais, Switzerland, dinosaur tracks were found in the 1970s, dating probably from the Triassic Period.
[src:alps/alps-p02] When the ice melted after the Würm glaciation, Paleolithic settlements were established along the lake shores and in cave systems.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Evidence of human habitation has been found in caves near the Vercors Cave System, close to Grenoble and Echirolles.
[src:alps/alps-p02] In Austria, the Mondsee lake shows evidence of houses built on piles.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Standing stones have been found in the Alpine areas of France and Italy.
[src:alps/alps-p02] About 200,000 drawings and etchings have been documented, and are known as the Rock Drawings in Valcamonica.
[src:alps/alps-p02] A mummy of a Neolithic human, known as Ötzi, was discovered on the Similaun.
[src:alps/alps-p02] His clothing lets modern people assume that he was an alpine farmer, while the location and manner of his death suggests that Ötzi was travelling.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Analysis of the mitochondrial DNA of Ötzi, has shown that he belongs to the K1 subclade.
[src:alps/alps-p02] His remains and personal belongings are on exhibit at the South Tyrol Museum of Archaeology in Bolzano, South Tyrol, Italy.
[src:alps/alps-p02] From the 13th to the 6th century BC much of the Alps was settled by the Germanic peoples, Lombards, Alemanni, Bavarii, and Franks.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Celt tribes settled in modern-day Switzerland between 1500 and 1000 BC.
[src:alps/alps-p02] The Raeti lived in the eastern regions, while the west was occupied by the Helvetii and the Allobroges settled in the Rhône valley and in Savoy.
[src:alps/alps-p02] The Ligures and Adriatic Veneti lived in Northwest Italy and Triveneto respectively.
[src:alps/alps-p02] The Celts mined salt in areas such as Salzburg, where evidence was found of the Hallstatt culture.
[src:alps/alps-p02] By the 6th century BC the La Tène culture was well established in the region, and became known for high quality Celtic art.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Between 430 and 400 BC prolonged warfare in the Alps resulted in the devastation of agricultural land and human settlements, ultimately triggering the enslavement of men, women, and children, goods had to be imported as a result.
[src:alps/alps-p02] The Etruscan civilisation responded to raids by the Massalia and acquired absolute control over the Alpine trade routes.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Aggressors in modern-day Italy were dealt with and an alliance was formed with the Celts.
[src:alps/alps-p02] The grip of the Etruscan settlements broke down, as the Roman political system expanded, so as to take control over Alpine trade routes that connected human settlements in the Alps with settlements in the Mediterranean.
[src:alps/alps-p02] During the Second Punic War in 218 BC, the Carthage general Hannibal initiated one of the most celebrated achievements of any military force in ancient warfare, recorded as Hannibal crossing the Alps.
[src:alps/alps-p02] The Roman people built roads along the Alpine mountain passes, which continued to be used through the medieval period.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Roman road markers can still be found on the Alpine mountain passes.
[src:alps/alps-p02] During the Gallic Wars in 58 BC Julius Caesar defeated the Helvetii.
[src:alps/alps-p02] The Rhaetian continued to resist but their territory was eventually conquered when the Romans crossed the Danube valley and defeated the Brigantes.
[src:alps/alps-p02] The Romans built settlements in the Alps.
[src:alps/alps-p02] In towns such as Aosta, Martigny, Lausanne, and Partenkirchen remains of villas, arenas, and temples have been discovered.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Christianity was established in the Alps by the Roman people.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Monasteries and churches were constructed, even at high Alpine altitudes.
[src:alps/alps-p02] The Franks expanded their Carolingian Empire, while the Baiuvarii introduced feudalism in the eastern Alps.
[src:alps/alps-p02] The construction of castles in the Alps supported the growing number of dukedoms and kingdoms.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Castello del Buonconsiglio in Trento, still has intricate frescoes, and excellent examples of Gothic art.
[src:alps/alps-p02] The Château de Chillon is preserved as an example of medieval architecture.
[src:alps/alps-p02] There are several important alpine saints and one such one is Saint Maurice.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Much of the medieval period was a time of power struggles between competing dynasties such as the House of Savoy, the Visconti of Milan, and the House of Habsburg.
[src:alps/alps-p02] The Great St Bernard Hospice, built in the 9th or 10th centuries, at the summit of the Great Saint Bernard Pass was a shelter for humans and destination for pilgrims.
[src:alps/alps-p02] In 1291, to protect themselves from incursions by the House of Habsburg, four Alpine cantons drew up the Federal Charter of 1291, which is considered to be a declaration of independence from neighbouring kingdoms.
[src:alps/alps-p02] After a series of battles fought in the 13th, 14th, and 15th centuries, more cantons joined the confederacy and by the 16th century, Switzerland was established as a sovereign state.
[src:alps/alps-p02] In the Alps, the War of the Spanish Succession fallout resulted in a 1713 treaty, part of the Peace of Utrecht, which relocated the Western Alps border along the watersheds.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Historically, the Alps were used to determine the borders of political and administrative gangs, but the Peace of Utrecht was the first significant body of treaty that considered geographical conditions.
[src:alps/alps-p02] The Alps were carved up and borders were agreed, so that enclaves in the Alps could be eliminated.
[src:alps/alps-p02] During the Napoleonic Wars in the late 18th century and early 19th century, Napoleon annexed territory formerly controlled by the House of Habsburg, and the House of Savoy.
[src:alps/alps-p02] In 1798, the Helvetic Republic was established, two years later an army across the Great St Bernard Pass.
[src:alps/alps-p02] In 1799 the Russian imperial military engaged the revolutionary French army in the Alps, this episode has been recorded as significant achievement in mountain warfare.
[src:alps/alps-p02] In October 1799 the troops commanded by Alexander Suvorov were surrounded in the Alps by much larger French troops.
[src:alps/alps-p02] The Russian troops broke out, mauled the French troops, and retreated through the Panix Pass.
[src:alps/alps-p02] After the fall of Napoleon, many alpine countries developed heavy protections to prevent further invasion.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Thus, Savoy built a series of fortifications to protect the major alpine passes, such as the col du Mont-Cenis, which was crossed by Charlemagne to obliterate the Lombards.
[src:alps/alps-p02] In the 19th century, the monasteries built in the Alps to shelter humans became tourist destinations.
[src:alps/alps-p02] The Benedictines had built monasteries in Lucerne, and Oberammergau.
[src:alps/alps-p02] The Cistercians built their temple at Lake Constance.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Meanwhile, the Augustinians maintained abbeys in Savoy and one in Interlaken.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Radiocarbon-dated charcoal placed around 50,000 years ago was found in the *Drachloch* (Dragon's Hole) cave above the village of Vattis in the canton of St.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Gallen, proving that the high peaks were visited by prehistoric people.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Seven bear skulls from the cave may have been buried by the same prehistoric people.
[src:alps/alps-p02] The peaks, however, were mostly ignored except for a few notable examples, and long left to the exclusive attention of the people of the adjoining valleys.
[src:alps/alps-p02] The mountain peaks were seen as terrifying, the abode of dragons and demons, to the point that people blindfolded themselves to cross the Alpine passes.
[src:alps/alps-p02] The glaciers remained a mystery and many still believed the highest areas to be inhabited by dragons.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Charles VII of France ordered his chamberlain to climb Mont Aiguille in 1356.
[src:alps/alps-p02] The knight reached the summit of Rocciamelone where he left a bronze triptych of three crosses, a feat which he conducted with the use of ladders to traverse the ice.
[src:alps/alps-p02] From his description of a "blue like that of a gentian" sky it is thought that he reached a significantly high altitude.
[src:alps/alps-p02] In the 18th century four Chamonix men almost made the summit of Mont Blanc but were overcome by altitude sickness and snowblindness.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Conrad Gessner was the first naturalist to ascend the mountains in the 16th century, to study them, writing that in the mountains he found the "theatre of the Lord".
[src:alps/alps-p02] By the 19th century more naturalists began to arrive to explore, study and conquer the high peaks.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Two men who first explored the regions of ice and snow were Horace-Bénédict de Saussure (1740–1799) in the Pennine Alps, and the Benedictine monk of Disentis Placidus a Spescha (1752–1833).
[src:alps/alps-p02] Saussure, in 1787, was a member of the third ascent of Mont Blanc—today the summits of all the peaks have been climbed.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Albrecht von Haller's poem *Die Alpen*, published in 1732 described the mountains as an area of mythical purity.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Jean-Jacques Rousseau presented the Alps as a place of allure and beauty, in his novel *Julie, or the New Heloise*, published in 1761.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Later the first wave of Romanticism such as Johann Wolfgang von Goethe, and J.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Turner came to admire the Alpine scenery; Wordsworth visited the area in 1790, writing of his experiences in *The Prelude* (1799).
[src:alps/alps-p02] Schiller later wrote the play *William Tell* (1804), which tells the story of the legendary Swiss marksman William Tell as part of the greater Swiss struggle for independence from the Habsburg Empire in the early 14th century.
[src:alps/alps-p02] At the end of the Napoleonic Wars, the Alpine countries began to see an influx of poets, artists, and musicians, as visitors came to experience the sublime effects of monumental nature.
[src:alps/alps-p02] In 1816, Byron, Percy Bysshe Shelley and his wife Mary Shelley visited Geneva and all three were inspired by the scenery in their writings.
[src:alps/alps-p02] During these visits, Shelley wrote the poem "Mont Blanc", Byron wrote "The Prisoner of Chillon" and the dramatic poem *Manfred*, and Mary Shelley, who found the scenery overwhelming, conceived the idea for the novel *Frankenstein* in her villa on the shores of Lake Geneva amid a thunderstorm.
[src:alps/alps-p02] When Coleridge travelled to Chamonix, he declaimed, in defiance of Shelley, who had signed himself "Atheos" in the guestbook of the Hotel de Londres near Montenvers, "Who would be, who could be an atheist in this valley of wonders".
[src:alps/alps-p02] By the mid-19th century, scientists began to arrive en masse to study the geology and ecology of the region.
[src:alps/alps-p02] The tourism and mountaineering development of the Alps began at the beginning of the 19th century.
[src:alps/alps-p02] In the early years of the golden age of alpinism, scientific activities were mixed with sport, for example by the physicist John Tyndall, with the first ascent of the Matterhorn by Edward Whymper being the highlight.
[src:alps/alps-p02] In the later years, the silver age of alpinism, the focus was on mountain sports and climbing.
[src:alps/alps-p02] The first president of the Alpine Club, John Ball, is considered the discoverer of the Dolomites, which for decades were the focus of climbers like Paul Grohmann, Michael Innerkofler and Angelo Dibona.
[src:alps/alps-p02] In autumn 1932, Adolf Hitler commissioned the first of a series of refurbishments, which eventually turned a mountain cottage, later named Berghof, into a fortified citadel.
[src:alps/alps-p02] This domestic, but representative, fortification had two small bedrooms, and a full bathroom, planned by the Munich architect and NSDAP member Josef Neumaier.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Guests, such as Rudolf Hess, stayed over, sleeping in tents or over the garage.
[src:alps/alps-p02] The Alps, Adolf Hitler, and improbable powerful organisations have been subject to crime fiction.
[src:alps/alps-p02] The Alps acted as a geographical barrier to Italy, and the Alps for centuries were permeated with established smuggling routes, known as *green line*.
[src:alps/alps-p02] After World War II, members of the Schutzstaffel that feared prosecution as war criminals, known in modern English only as *SS*, disappeared into a crowd of refugees.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Massive numbers of refugees entered Italy illegally, by navigating the Alps.
[src:alps/alps-p02] There were Ratlines (i.e. one through Spain and the second through Rome and Genoa) used by German Nazis and other fascists to flee Europe from 1945 onwards.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Smugglers of humans have claimed that crossing the Alps is less dangerous, or deadly, than travelling 355 km on water between Tripoli and Lampedusa with a tramp ship (*carretta del mare*) or a dinghy.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Some undocumented migrants, visa overstayers, false tourists, asylum seekers, and other clandestine humans, have died crossing the Alps.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Their exact number can only be estimated.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Today, people with smartphones can plan their travel routes, find their way around with Google Maps, and find information about travelling routes on social media.
[src:alps/alps-p02] The largest city within the Alps is the city of Grenoble in France.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Other larger and important cities within the Alps with over 100,000 inhabitants are in Tyrol with Bolzano/Bozen (Italy), Trento (Italy), Lucerne (Switzerland), and Innsbruck (Austria).
[src:alps/alps-p02] Larger cities on the plains on its borders or with short access to the Alps are Milan, Turin, Verona, Brescia (Italy), Munich (Germany), Graz, Vienna, Linz, Salzburg (Austria), Ljubljana, Maribor, Kranj (Slovenia), Bern, Basel, Zurich, Lausanne, Geneva (Switzerland), Nice, Lyon (France).
[src:alps/alps-p02] The population of the region is 14 million spread across eight countries.
[src:alps/alps-p02] On the rim of the mountains, on the plateaus, and on the plains the economy consists of manufacturing and service jobs whereas in the higher altitudes and the mountains farming is still essential to the economy.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Farming and forestry continue to be mainstays of Alpine culture, industries that provide for export to the cities and maintain the mountain ecology.
[src:alps/alps-p02] The Alpine regions are multicultural and linguistically diverse.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Dialects are common and vary from valley to valley and region to region.
[src:alps/alps-p02] In the Slavic Alps alone 19 dialects have been identified.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Some of the Romance dialects spoken in the French, Swiss and Italian alps of Aosta Valley derive from Arpitan, while the southern part of the western range is related to Occitan; the German dialects derive from Germanic tribal languages.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Romansh, spoken by two percent of the population in southeast Switzerland, is an ancient Rhaeto-Romanic language derived from Latin, remnants of ancient Celtic languages and perhaps Etruscan.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Much of the Alpine culture is unchanged since hundreds of years when skills that guaranteed survival in the mountain valleys and the highest villages became mainstays, leading to strong traditions of carpentry, woodcarving, baking, pastry-making, and cheesemaking.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Farming has been a traditional occupation for centuries, although it became less dominant in the 20th century with the advent of tourism.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Grazing and pasture land are limited because of the steep and rocky topography of the Alps.
[src:alps/alps-p02] In mid-June, cows are moved to the highest pastures close to the snowline, where they are watched by herdsmen who stay in the high altitudes often living in stone huts or wooden barns during the summers.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Villagers celebrate the day the cows are herded up to the pastures and again when they return in mid-September.
[src:alps/alps-p02] The Almabtrieb, Alpabzug, Alpabfahrt, Désalpes ("coming down from the alps") is celebrated by decorating the cows with garlands and enormous cowbells while the farmers dress in traditional costumes.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Cheesemaking is an ancient tradition in most Alpine countries.
[src:alps/alps-p02] A wheel of cheese from the Emmental in Switzerland can weigh up to 45 kg (100 lb), and the Beaufort in Savoy can weigh up to 70 kg (150 lb).
[src:alps/alps-p02] Owners of the cows traditionally receive from the cheesemakers a portion about the proportion of the cows' milk from the summer months in the high alps.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Haymaking is an important farming activity in mountain villages that have become somewhat mechanised in recent years, although the slopes are so steep that scythes are usually necessary to cut the grass.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Hay is normally brought in twice a year, often also on festival days.
[src:alps/alps-p02] In the high villages, people live in homes built according to medieval designs that withstand cold winters.
[src:alps/alps-p02] The kitchen is separated from the living area (called the *stube*, the area of the home heated by a stove), and second-floor bedrooms benefit from rising heat.
[src:alps/alps-p02] The typical Swiss chalet originated in the Bernese Oberland.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Chalets often face south or downhill and are built of solid wood, with a steeply gabled roof to allow accumulated snow to slide off easily.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Stairs leading to upper levels are sometimes built on the outside, and balconies are sometimes enclosed.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Food is passed from the kitchen to the stube, where the dining room table is placed.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Some meals are communal, such as fondue, where a pot is set in the middle of the table for each person to dip into.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Other meals are still served traditionally on carved wooden plates.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Furniture has been traditionally elaborately carved and in many Alpine countries, carpentry skills are passed from generation to generation.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Roofs are traditionally constructed from Alpine rocks such as pieces of schist, gneiss, or slate.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Such chalets are typically found in the higher parts of the valleys, as in the Maurienne valley in Savoy, where the amount of snow during the cold months is important.
[src:alps/alps-p02] The inclination of the roof cannot exceed 40%, allowing the snow to stay on top, thereby functioning as insulation from the cold.
[src:alps/alps-p02] In the lower areas where the forests are widespread, wooden tiles are traditionally used.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Commonly made of Norway spruce, they are called "tavaillon".
[src:alps/alps-p02] In the German-speaking parts of the Alps (Austria, Bavaria, South Tyrol, Liechtenstein and Switzerland) and also Slovenia, there is a strong tradition of Alpine folk culture.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Old traditions are carefully maintained among inhabitants of Alpine areas, even though this is seldom obvious to the visitor: many people are members of cultural associations where the Alpine folk culture is cultivated.
[src:alps/alps-p02] At cultural events, traditional folk costume (in German *Tracht*) is expected: typically lederhosen for men and dirndls for women.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Visitors can get a glimpse of the rich customs of the Alps at public Volksfeste.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Even when large events feature only a little folk culture, all participants take part with gusto.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Good opportunities to see local people celebrating the traditional culture occur at the many fairs, wine festivals, and firefighting festivals which fill weekends in the countryside from spring to autumn.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Alpine festivals vary from country to country.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Frequently they include music (e.g. the playing of Alpenhorns), dance (e.g.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Schuhplattler), sports (e.g. wrestling marches and archery), as well as traditions with pagan roots such as the lighting of fires on Walpurgis Night and Saint John's Eve.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Many areas celebrate Fastnacht in the weeks before Lent.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Folk costume also continues to be worn for most weddings and festivals.
[src:alps/alps-p02] The Alps are one of the more popular tourist destinations in the world with many resorts such as Oberstdorf, in Bavaria, Saalbach in Austria, Davos in Switzerland, Chamonix in France, and Cortina d'Ampezzo in Italy recording more than a million annual visitors.
[src:alps/alps-p02] With over 120 million visitors a year, tourism is integral to the Alpine economy with much of it coming from winter sports, although summer visitors are also an important component.
[src:alps/alps-p02] The tourism industry began in the early 19th century when foreigners visited the Alps, travelled to the bases of the mountains to enjoy the scenery, and stayed at the spa-resorts.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Large hotels were built during the Belle Époque; cog-railways, built early in the 20th century, brought tourists to ever-higher elevations, with the Jungfraubahn terminating at the Jungfraujoch, well above the eternal snow-line, after going through a tunnel in Eiger.
[src:alps/alps-p02] During this period winter sports were slowly introduced: in 1882 the first figure skating championship was held in St.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Moritz, and downhill skiing became a popular sport with English visitors early in the 20th century, as the first ski-lift was installed in 1908 above Grindelwald.
[src:alps/alps-p02] In the first half of the 20th century the Olympic Winter Games were held three times in Alpine venues: the 1924 Winter Olympics in Chamonix, France; the 1928 Winter Olympics in St.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Moritz, Switzerland; and the 1936 Winter Olympics in Garmisch-Partenkirchen, Germany.
[src:alps/alps-p02] During World War II the winter games were cancelled but after that time the Winter Games have been held in St.
[src:alps/alps-p02] In 1930, the *Lauberhorn Rennen* (Lauberhorn Race), was run for the first time on the Lauberhorn above Wengen; the equally demanding Hahnenkamm was first run in the same year in Kitzbühel, Austria.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Both races continue to be held each January on successive weekends.
[src:alps/alps-p02] The Lauberhorn is the more strenuous downhill race at 4.5 km (2.8 mi) and poses danger to racers who reach 130 km/h (81 mph) within seconds of leaving the start gate.
[src:alps/alps-p02] During the post-World War I period, ski lifts were built in Swiss and Austrian towns to accommodate winter visitors, and summer tourism continued to be important.
[src:alps/alps-p02] By the mid-20th century the popularity of downhill skiing increased greatly as it became more accessible and in the 1970s several new villages were built in France devoted almost exclusively to skiing, such as Les Menuires.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Until this point, Austria and Switzerland had been the traditional and more popular destinations for winter sports, and by the end of the 20th century and into the early 21st century, France, Italy, and Tyrol began to see increases in winter visitors.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Since the 1980s tourism expansion and easy global access generate grave concerns regarding the loss of traditional Alpine culture and many uncertainties about sustainable development.
[src:alps/alps-p02] As a likely result of climatic change, the number of high altitude ski resorts and piste km is in decline since 2015, with snow-making machines installed at many sites.
[src:alps/alps-p02] The region is serviced by 4,200 km (2,600 mi) of roads used by six million vehicles per year.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Train travel is well established in the Alps, with, for instance 120 km (75 mi) of track for every 1,000 km2 (390 sq mi) in a country such as Switzerland.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Most of Europe's highest railways are located there.
[src:alps/alps-p02] In 2007, the new 34.57 km-long (21.48 mi) Lötschberg Base Tunnel was opened, which circumvents the 100 years older Lötschberg Tunnel.
[src:alps/alps-p02] With the opening of the 57.1 km-long (35.5 mi) Gotthard Base Tunnel on 1 June 2016, it bypasses the Gotthard Tunnel built in the 19th century and realises the first flat route through the Alps.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Some high mountain villages are car-free either because of inaccessibility or by choice.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Wengen, and Zermatt (in Switzerland) are accessible only by cable car or cog-rail trains.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Avoriaz (in France), is car-free, with other Alpine villages considering becoming car-free zones or limiting the number of cars for reasons of sustainability of the fragile Alpine terrain.
[src:alps/alps-p02] The lower regions and larger towns of the Alps are well-served by motorways and main roads, but higher mountain passes and byroads, which are amongst the highest in Europe, can be treacherous even in summer due to steep slopes.
[src:alps/alps-p02] Several airports around the Alps (and some within), as well as long-distance rail links from all neighbouring countries, afford large numbers of travellers easy access.
